00:01:55.790 --> 00:01:59.630
He holds a PhD in social and
cultural studies in education

00:01:59.630 --> 00:02:02.040
and a bachelor of arts
degree in literature,

00:02:02.040 --> 00:02:03.800
both from UC Berkeley.

00:02:03.800 --> 00:02:06.950
So thank you so much to
Jeff, and please welcome.

00:02:06.950 --> 00:02:10.404
[APPLAUSE]

00:02:10.404 --> 00:02:11.820
JEFF DUNCAN-ANDRADE:
Good morning.

00:02:11.820 --> 00:02:13.290
AUDIENCE: Good morning.

00:02:13.290 --> 00:02:13.900
JEFF DUNCAN-ANDRADE:
That's way better

00:02:13.900 --> 00:02:14.983
than my high school class.

00:02:14.983 --> 00:02:16.260
[LAUGHTER]

00:02:17.550 --> 00:02:25.270
So the talk that I was
asked to do today really

00:02:25.270 --> 00:02:32.500
emerged probably about 18
months ago as the result of work

00:02:32.500 --> 00:02:36.730
that I'd been doing for the
last five to seven years

00:02:36.730 --> 00:02:42.610
pretty consistently, which is
I'm consistently getting called

00:02:42.610 --> 00:02:47.890
by districts, by schools,
by charter groups,

00:02:47.890 --> 00:02:53.950
by orgs like Google,
like Facebook to help

00:02:53.950 --> 00:02:59.410
them think through their equity
plans or their equity efforts.

00:02:59.410 --> 00:03:02.050
So I'm in a room
full of educators,

00:03:02.050 --> 00:03:05.710
and I'm quite certain that
your district or school

00:03:05.710 --> 00:03:10.270
group is also now
all about equity,

00:03:10.270 --> 00:03:14.140
because this is all the rage
all over the country, right?

00:03:14.140 --> 00:03:15.830
We're going to do equity.

00:03:15.830 --> 00:03:18.580
So the first thing that
I typically say to people

00:03:18.580 --> 00:03:23.800
is that if you have an equity
office or an equity officer,

00:03:23.800 --> 00:03:25.795
then you know you
don't have equity.

00:03:25.795 --> 00:03:26.725
[LAUGHTER]

00:03:28.120 --> 00:03:34.540
Because equity is everybody
on deck all the time.

00:03:34.540 --> 00:03:39.480
Everybody's an equity officer,
or nobody's an equity officer.

00:03:39.480 --> 00:03:41.331
Now you've got to
start somewhere, right?

00:03:41.331 --> 00:03:43.330
So you're probably going
to start with an equity

00:03:43.330 --> 00:03:46.840
officer or an equity
office or an equity plan,

00:03:46.840 --> 00:03:49.480
and this is usually the
place where I get inserted.

00:03:49.480 --> 00:03:54.820
So I get asked to be a
thought partner, a consultant,

00:03:54.820 --> 00:03:59.980
a co-constructor of
districts' equity plans.

00:03:59.980 --> 00:04:03.920
And so I've been doing this
now for quite some time.

00:04:03.920 --> 00:04:09.100
And it got to the point where
it was so common that when

00:04:09.100 --> 00:04:11.650
I was having these
conversations and reading

00:04:11.650 --> 00:04:15.250
these strategic plans that I
would see these two words used

00:04:15.250 --> 00:04:21.279
interchangeably, that I decided
that I wanted to develop

00:04:21.279 --> 00:04:24.820
a talk that helped
people disentangle

00:04:24.820 --> 00:04:29.380
the concept of
equality and equity.

00:04:29.380 --> 00:04:33.250
Because equality and equity
are fundamentally different,

00:04:33.250 --> 00:04:35.560
and what I find in
a lot of schools

00:04:35.560 --> 00:04:39.160
that are saying they're trying
to pivot towards equity,

00:04:39.160 --> 00:04:41.440
they use these terms
interchangeably

00:04:41.440 --> 00:04:43.750
because they haven't
actually spent the time

00:04:43.750 --> 00:04:47.410
to understand what
equity means, and how

00:04:47.410 --> 00:04:50.950
fundamentally different an
equitable approach to schooling

00:04:50.950 --> 00:04:56.410
in this nation would be than
an equal education system.

00:04:56.410 --> 00:04:59.740
Now how do we even
land on a conversation

00:04:59.740 --> 00:05:01.480
about an equal education system?

00:05:03.990 --> 00:05:06.129
What's the Supreme
Court decision?

00:05:06.129 --> 00:05:07.170
AUDIENCE: Brown v. Board.

00:05:07.170 --> 00:05:07.940
JEFF DUNCAN-ANDRADE:
OK, Brown v. Board.

00:05:07.940 --> 00:05:09.220
What year is that?

00:05:09.220 --> 00:05:10.140
AUDIENCE: 1956?

00:05:10.140 --> 00:05:12.210
JEFF DUNCAN-ANDRADE: 1954, OK?

00:05:12.210 --> 00:05:13.350
Brown v. Board.

00:05:13.350 --> 00:05:15.870
Brown v. Board,
Supreme Court decision

00:05:15.870 --> 00:05:21.080
legislated against another
Supreme Court decision.

00:05:21.080 --> 00:05:24.730
So we had to say that
we were committed

00:05:24.730 --> 00:05:27.090
to equality because why?

00:05:27.090 --> 00:05:28.520
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:05:28.520 --> 00:05:31.020
JEFF DUNCAN-ANDRADE: Because
we were committed to inequality

00:05:31.020 --> 00:05:34.410
before, formally, right?

00:05:34.410 --> 00:05:36.415
And what Supreme Court
decision was that?

00:05:36.415 --> 00:05:37.790
AUDIENCE: Plessy
versus Ferguson.

00:05:37.790 --> 00:05:40.180
JEFF DUNCAN-ANDRADE:
OK Plessy v. Ferguson.

00:05:40.180 --> 00:05:43.450
Plessy v. Ferguson
Supreme Court decision

00:05:43.450 --> 00:05:48.700
legislated racial segregation
as the law of the land, right?

00:05:48.700 --> 00:05:51.310
Plessy said-- the
Plessy decision

00:05:51.310 --> 00:05:56.410
said that separate is equal.

00:05:56.410 --> 00:05:58.150
That's why we have Brown.

00:05:58.150 --> 00:06:02.140
So we get to 1954, and
the Brown decision says,

00:06:02.140 --> 00:06:06.230
no, separate by
definition is unequal.

00:06:06.230 --> 00:06:09.180
We are now in 2017.

00:06:09.180 --> 00:06:13.410
So six-plus decades of
a national commitment

00:06:13.410 --> 00:06:20.365
to an equal education system,
to desegregated, racially

00:06:20.365 --> 00:06:22.930
desegregated education system.

00:06:22.930 --> 00:06:24.650
Six decades.

00:06:24.650 --> 00:06:28.180
Highest policy body
in the land has

00:06:28.180 --> 00:06:33.890
said that racial segregation
in schools is illegal.

00:06:33.890 --> 00:06:37.090
Six decades plus in.

00:06:37.090 --> 00:06:39.760
Any guesses on how
much progress we've

00:06:39.760 --> 00:06:43.360
made on racially
desegregating city schools?

00:06:43.360 --> 00:06:45.980
You just jumped right
in with the settle, OK?

00:06:45.980 --> 00:06:46.772
AUDIENCE: Negative.

00:06:46.772 --> 00:06:48.021
JEFF DUNCAN-ANDRADE: Negative.

00:06:48.021 --> 00:06:49.131
You think-- what?

00:06:49.131 --> 00:06:49.630
[LAUGHTER]

00:06:49.630 --> 00:06:51.490
AUDIENCE: I think
it's gotten worse.

00:06:51.490 --> 00:06:52.860
JEFF DUNCAN-ANDRADE: You
think it's gone backwards.

00:06:52.860 --> 00:06:53.980
Let's do "The Price is Right."

00:06:53.980 --> 00:06:56.110
You can't actually bid negative
on "The Price is Right,"

00:06:56.110 --> 00:06:56.693
so you're out.

00:06:56.693 --> 00:06:59.590
[LAUGHTER]

00:06:59.590 --> 00:07:01.540
Anybody think we've
made any progress?

00:07:01.540 --> 00:07:02.360
5%?

00:07:02.360 --> 00:07:03.300
10%?

00:07:03.300 --> 00:07:05.320
OK, your hand went up.

00:07:05.320 --> 00:07:06.812
OK, you're in the game now.

00:07:06.812 --> 00:07:08.230
AUDIENCE: You brought
yourself in the game.

00:07:08.230 --> 00:07:09.400
JEFF DUNCAN-ANDRADE: Yeah, you
brought yourself in the game.

00:07:09.400 --> 00:07:10.390
OK, what do you think?

00:07:10.390 --> 00:07:11.860
How much?

00:07:11.860 --> 00:07:12.520
5%?

00:07:12.520 --> 00:07:13.020
10%?

00:07:13.020 --> 00:07:14.230
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]?

00:07:14.230 --> 00:07:15.631
JEFF DUNCAN-ANDRADE: 10%.

00:07:15.631 --> 00:07:17.237
OK, anybody want to go higher?

00:07:17.237 --> 00:07:18.400
AUDIENCE: I say 20%.

00:07:18.400 --> 00:07:20.740
JEFF DUNCAN-ANDRADE: 20%
racial desegregation.

00:07:20.740 --> 00:07:21.329
AUDIENCE: 21%.

00:07:21.329 --> 00:07:22.370
JEFF DUNCAN-ANDRADE: 21%.

00:07:22.370 --> 00:07:22.870
[LAUGHTER]

00:07:22.870 --> 00:07:24.470
Yeah, now we got the game going.

00:07:24.470 --> 00:07:26.350
Now we got the game going.

00:07:26.350 --> 00:07:29.170
OK.

00:07:29.170 --> 00:07:29.680
No.

00:07:29.680 --> 00:07:32.490
You're right.

00:07:32.490 --> 00:07:33.275
Negative.

00:07:33.275 --> 00:07:34.400
No you didn't say negative.

00:07:34.400 --> 00:07:35.090
You said zero.

00:07:35.090 --> 00:07:35.490
AUDIENCE: I said negative.

00:07:35.490 --> 00:07:36.270
JEFF DUNCAN-ANDRADE: Oh, OK.

00:07:36.270 --> 00:07:36.590
All right.

00:07:36.590 --> 00:07:36.920
You're right.

00:07:36.920 --> 00:07:37.500
You win.

00:07:37.500 --> 00:07:38.280
[LAUGHTER]

00:07:38.280 --> 00:07:40.700
It's the new "Price is Right."

00:07:40.700 --> 00:07:42.980
City schools are more
racially segregated

00:07:42.980 --> 00:07:44.567
now than they were
before the Supreme

00:07:44.567 --> 00:07:45.650
Court said that's illegal.

00:07:48.490 --> 00:07:51.110
There's a man named
Gary Orfield who's

00:07:51.110 --> 00:07:56.030
considered one of the nation's
leading educational historians.

00:07:56.030 --> 00:07:59.684
Lawyer by trade, he's at UCLA.

00:07:59.684 --> 00:08:01.100
He was at Harvard
for a long time.

00:08:01.100 --> 00:08:02.766
When he started this
project, he started

00:08:02.766 --> 00:08:05.520
the Harvard Civil Rights
Project, which every--

00:08:05.520 --> 00:08:09.080
on every decade anniversary
of the Brown decision,

00:08:09.080 --> 00:08:11.210
his research team
releases a report

00:08:11.210 --> 00:08:13.850
that tracks the
progress of our efforts

00:08:13.850 --> 00:08:15.920
to racially desegregate schools.

00:08:15.920 --> 00:08:19.900
On the 60th anniversary of
Brown, he's now at UCLA.

00:08:19.900 --> 00:08:23.660
So of course, the project is
now called the UCLA Civil Rights

00:08:23.660 --> 00:08:24.240
Project.

00:08:24.240 --> 00:08:25.196
[LAUGHTER]

00:08:26.630 --> 00:08:29.000
And on the 60th
anniversary of Brown,

00:08:29.000 --> 00:08:31.040
they release their
latest report,

00:08:31.040 --> 00:08:35.840
and the data reveals that
schools are now more racially

00:08:35.840 --> 00:08:37.159
segregated.

00:08:37.159 --> 00:08:39.380
We've gone backwards.

00:08:39.380 --> 00:08:43.720
That, y'all, is the
value of a policy.

00:08:43.720 --> 00:08:47.020
We cannot policy
our way out of this.

00:08:47.020 --> 00:08:49.630
Now that doesn't mean
policy doesn't matter.

00:08:49.630 --> 00:08:51.190
Y'all are educators.

00:08:51.190 --> 00:08:53.120
I'm a 25-year vet
of the classroom.

00:08:53.120 --> 00:08:55.100
I know policy matters.

00:08:55.100 --> 00:08:56.590
I know my life
was very different

00:08:56.590 --> 00:08:59.800
when we had No Child Left
Behind than it was before we

00:08:59.800 --> 00:09:01.354
had No Child Left Behind.

00:09:01.354 --> 00:09:03.520
There's always been a bunch
of children left behind.

00:09:03.520 --> 00:09:04.996
[LAUGHTER]

00:09:05.980 --> 00:09:13.160
So the pivot from
an equal education

00:09:13.160 --> 00:09:16.820
system, which we have
failed miserably at--

00:09:16.820 --> 00:09:18.680
and everyone in this
room knows because it's

00:09:18.680 --> 00:09:21.440
the worst-kept secret
in the country.

00:09:21.440 --> 00:09:26.630
Everyone in this room knows that
wealthy children, middle class

00:09:26.630 --> 00:09:29.720
children that attend
public schools

00:09:29.720 --> 00:09:32.360
attend public schools
that are fundamentally

00:09:32.360 --> 00:09:36.820
different than the schools
that poor children attend,

00:09:36.820 --> 00:09:38.780
the children of color attend.

00:09:38.780 --> 00:09:41.340
Everyone knows that.

00:09:41.340 --> 00:09:46.580
And equality, an equal education
system is like "Sesame Street"

00:09:46.580 --> 00:09:47.670
shit.

00:09:47.670 --> 00:09:50.670
One for you, one for me,
one for you, one for me.

00:09:50.670 --> 00:09:53.430
And we haven't even
pulled that off.

00:09:53.430 --> 00:09:57.791
And now we're talking
about pivoting to equity.

00:09:57.791 --> 00:10:02.100
And equity's a much different,
much more complex lift.

00:10:02.100 --> 00:10:05.460
So if you go move
to equity, you've

00:10:05.460 --> 00:10:08.780
got to first really
invest in understanding

00:10:08.780 --> 00:10:12.110
the difference between
an equal education system

00:10:12.110 --> 00:10:16.820
and what it's produced for
us and an equitable education

00:10:16.820 --> 00:10:21.140
system and what its potential
is to produce for us.

00:10:21.140 --> 00:10:24.050
Now the way I've come
to understand this,

00:10:24.050 --> 00:10:28.792
and probably at the deepest
level of my understanding

00:10:28.792 --> 00:10:36.970
is because I have
a live experiment

00:10:36.970 --> 00:10:40.360
in my home about the difference
between equality and equity,

00:10:40.360 --> 00:10:43.200
because I have twin boys.

00:10:43.200 --> 00:10:46.420
These are my sons,
Amaru and Taiyari.

00:10:46.420 --> 00:10:48.900
And I shit you not,
I'm not making this up.

00:10:48.900 --> 00:10:50.820
I dare you to even
try to make this up.

00:10:50.820 --> 00:10:53.485
Last night, I'm on the
phone because I'm--

00:10:53.485 --> 00:10:55.110
if you look at my
car right now, you're

00:10:55.110 --> 00:10:57.630
going to see a suitcase,
because I flew in last night

00:10:57.630 --> 00:10:59.410
and then yeah.

00:10:59.410 --> 00:10:59.910
All that.

00:10:59.910 --> 00:11:00.409
OK.

00:11:00.409 --> 00:11:06.180
So I'm on the phone with
my son on my travels home

00:11:06.180 --> 00:11:07.290
and he says--

00:11:07.290 --> 00:11:09.680
he's about to go to bed.

00:11:09.680 --> 00:11:12.270
And I said, what
are you doing, son?

00:11:12.270 --> 00:11:19.950
And he said, I'm asking Google
if Han Solo and the Millennium

00:11:19.950 --> 00:11:24.630
Falcon and Stormtroopers
and Princess Leia

00:11:24.630 --> 00:11:25.710
can all be friends.

00:11:25.710 --> 00:11:27.470
[LAUGHTER]

00:11:28.350 --> 00:11:29.760
And I said, you're asking who?

00:11:29.760 --> 00:11:32.460
And he said-- then
he quotes Bush.

00:11:32.460 --> 00:11:34.080
He says, "the Google."

00:11:34.080 --> 00:11:37.960
[LAUGHTER]

00:11:37.960 --> 00:11:40.640
And I said, son, I'm
probably not going

00:11:40.640 --> 00:11:43.020
to be there in the
morning when you wake up.

00:11:43.020 --> 00:11:44.190
And he says, why not?

00:11:44.190 --> 00:11:46.080
And I said, because I'm
going to the Google.

00:11:46.080 --> 00:11:48.480
[LAUGHTER]

00:11:48.480 --> 00:11:51.360
[APPLAUSE]

00:11:51.360 --> 00:11:54.090
And he's so juiced.

00:11:54.090 --> 00:11:56.490
And then I get out the
house this morning--

00:11:56.490 --> 00:11:59.160
and this is partially
the reason why I'm late--

00:11:59.160 --> 00:12:02.642
and I forgot my belt.
And I get down the block,

00:12:02.642 --> 00:12:03.600
and I'm like, oh, shit.

00:12:03.600 --> 00:12:06.024
I forgot my belt and my
pants are falling down.

00:12:06.024 --> 00:12:08.190
I can't be at the Google
with my pants falling down.

00:12:08.190 --> 00:12:09.220
[LAUGHTER]

00:12:09.220 --> 00:12:14.240
So I go back to the house to get
my belt, and my sons are there.

00:12:14.240 --> 00:12:16.160
And my son runs up to me.

00:12:16.160 --> 00:12:17.340
He's like, Daddy, it's--

00:12:17.340 --> 00:12:20.750
I have-- he's like, did
you go to the Google?

00:12:20.750 --> 00:12:21.680
And I said, no, son.

00:12:21.680 --> 00:12:22.200
I'm going.

00:12:22.200 --> 00:12:24.840
And he says, Daddy, take
a picture with the Google.

00:12:24.840 --> 00:12:25.820
[LAUGHTER]

00:12:25.820 --> 00:12:26.699
OK, so y'all have--

00:12:26.699 --> 00:12:28.490
Googlers, you've got
to help me figure out,

00:12:28.490 --> 00:12:30.010
like, what does
that actually mean?

00:12:30.010 --> 00:12:30.510
How do you--

00:12:30.510 --> 00:12:31.620
[LAUGHTER]

00:12:31.620 --> 00:12:34.670
He thinks the Google
is a person, OK?

00:12:34.670 --> 00:12:36.990
