00:26:29.190 --> 00:26:32.500
with children than
their families.

00:26:32.500 --> 00:26:38.410
And yet we have produced one of
the most unpeaceful societies

00:26:38.410 --> 00:26:43.070
in the world, despite
all that investment.

00:26:43.070 --> 00:26:46.070
The 2016 Index came
out not long ago,

00:26:46.070 --> 00:26:47.450
and we're trending
the wrong way.

00:26:47.450 --> 00:26:49.910
We're now 103.

00:26:49.910 --> 00:26:53.150
And what I find particularly
interesting about our ranking

00:26:53.150 --> 00:26:56.250
is who's ahead of us.

00:26:56.250 --> 00:26:57.840
Nation states that
we are regularly

00:26:57.840 --> 00:27:02.700
on public record for
critiquing their total state

00:27:02.700 --> 00:27:08.040
of discontinuity, disarray,
injustice, and lack of peace.

00:27:08.040 --> 00:27:10.710
And yet according to
the Peace Index that

00:27:10.710 --> 00:27:15.330
is used by the globe's
largest and most

00:27:15.330 --> 00:27:19.680
committed organizations to
studying and promoting peace,

00:27:19.680 --> 00:27:21.800
we are doing worse than them.

00:27:21.800 --> 00:27:26.850
Now I would venture a guess that
few, if any people in this room

00:27:26.850 --> 00:27:30.250
live at 103.

00:27:30.250 --> 00:27:33.100
In point of fact, most
of us in this room

00:27:33.100 --> 00:27:36.150
live somewhere
around the top 20.

00:27:36.150 --> 00:27:40.950
Which means what if we're 103?

00:27:40.950 --> 00:27:43.250
What does it mean for the
kids that are struggling

00:27:43.250 --> 00:27:44.390
the most in your school?

00:27:44.390 --> 00:27:45.660
Where do they live?

00:27:45.660 --> 00:27:46.580
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:27:46.580 --> 00:27:49.330
JEFF DUNCAN-ANDRADE:
Yeah, they live at 140.

00:27:49.330 --> 00:27:52.580
Because for us to get to
103 in the aggregate when

00:27:52.580 --> 00:27:55.580
all these people in
this room live at 20

00:27:55.580 --> 00:28:00.650
means that somebody else is
way below 103 to get us to 103.

00:28:00.650 --> 00:28:06.140
And that disconnect is what
Bryan Stevenson calls proximity

00:28:06.140 --> 00:28:09.590
to pain or a lack of
proximity to pain.

00:28:09.590 --> 00:28:14.030
Bryan Stevenson, another
person that Google's made

00:28:14.030 --> 00:28:17.300
a lot of investment in.

00:28:17.300 --> 00:28:21.120
Consider the nation's
leading death row lawyer.

00:28:21.120 --> 00:28:22.830
For my money, has
the best analysis

00:28:22.830 --> 00:28:26.100
of race going in the country.

00:28:26.100 --> 00:28:29.596
Says that the problem that we
have in this society right now

00:28:29.596 --> 00:28:31.470
is that most of the
people that are designing

00:28:31.470 --> 00:28:34.500
the solutions for pain
aren't proximate to the pain

00:28:34.500 --> 00:28:36.210
that they're trying to relieve.

00:28:36.210 --> 00:28:38.130
And when you're not
proximate to the pain,

00:28:38.130 --> 00:28:41.010
you come up with solutions that
are most convenient for you

00:28:41.010 --> 00:28:42.570
not in pain.

00:28:42.570 --> 00:28:45.450
But when you get
proximate to the pain,

00:28:45.450 --> 00:28:50.770
the solutions you come up
with are very, very different.

00:28:50.770 --> 00:28:52.800
But most of us are
serving children

00:28:52.800 --> 00:28:57.930
that are living somewhere around
130 or 140 while we live in 20.

00:28:57.930 --> 00:29:03.810
And that disconnect leads us to
create schools that disconnect

00:29:03.810 --> 00:29:05.520
the kids that most need it.

00:29:05.520 --> 00:29:08.550
How do we get
proximate to the pain

00:29:08.550 --> 00:29:11.940
that we're actually trying to
relieve in our service of youth

00:29:11.940 --> 00:29:13.580
and families?

00:29:13.580 --> 00:29:16.200
1854.

00:29:16.200 --> 00:29:20.430
London, England was on
the verge of collapse.

00:29:20.430 --> 00:29:24.590
Massive outbreak of
cholera, so much so

00:29:24.590 --> 00:29:29.720
that city officials believed
that they would lose the city.

00:29:29.720 --> 00:29:32.680
In a last ditch
effort to save London,

00:29:32.680 --> 00:29:36.750
they sequestered the leading
medical officials in the city,

00:29:36.750 --> 00:29:41.350
locked them in a room, sat
them at a table and said,

00:29:41.350 --> 00:29:43.840
you're not coming out
of here until you've

00:29:43.840 --> 00:29:48.160
got the solution for
cholera for this city.

00:29:48.160 --> 00:29:51.060
They sat in there and knocked
around ideas, strategized,

00:29:51.060 --> 00:29:54.352
whiteboarded it.

00:29:54.352 --> 00:29:56.810
One of the doctors sitting at
the table stands up and says,

00:29:56.810 --> 00:29:58.035
this is absurd.

00:29:58.035 --> 00:30:00.500
They said, what do you mean?

00:30:00.500 --> 00:30:02.850
He says, every single
solution we come up

00:30:02.850 --> 00:30:06.960
with defaults us to cholera.

00:30:06.960 --> 00:30:08.460
We're coming up
with ways that we're

00:30:08.460 --> 00:30:11.290
going to live with cholera.

00:30:11.290 --> 00:30:14.500
How we're going to
manage our suffering.

00:30:14.500 --> 00:30:17.065
They said, yeah.

00:30:17.065 --> 00:30:19.780
He says, I didn't sign
up to be a medical doctor

00:30:19.780 --> 00:30:22.150
to live in a state of sickness.

00:30:22.150 --> 00:30:24.580
I signed up to be
medical doctor to create

00:30:24.580 --> 00:30:26.410
the conditions of wellness.

00:30:26.410 --> 00:30:29.110
And I'm OK with
treating sickness,

00:30:29.110 --> 00:30:30.550
but that's not the end game.

00:30:30.550 --> 00:30:33.640
The end game is total wellness.

00:30:33.640 --> 00:30:36.050
They said, well, you're
not being realistic.

00:30:36.050 --> 00:30:38.220
You're not looking at the data.

00:30:38.220 --> 00:30:42.190
And I hear this said to school
leaders and classroom teachers

00:30:42.190 --> 00:30:46.690
all the time when we start
talking about a radical pivot,

00:30:46.690 --> 00:30:49.810
fundamentally
changing what we do

00:30:49.810 --> 00:30:51.609
on the day-to-day
in schools, how

00:30:51.609 --> 00:30:53.650
we interact with the
children that we continually

00:30:53.650 --> 00:30:55.120
fail to serve.

00:30:55.120 --> 00:30:57.680
Hard pivots.

00:30:57.680 --> 00:31:01.972
I hear them told that
they're not being pragmatic,

00:31:01.972 --> 00:31:05.470
that they're not
looking at the data,

00:31:05.470 --> 00:31:08.070
just like they told
this medical doctor.

00:31:08.070 --> 00:31:10.071
So he looks back
at his colleagues

00:31:10.071 --> 00:31:11.570
and he says, if
that's what it needs

00:31:11.570 --> 00:31:14.400
be part of your
medical association,

00:31:14.400 --> 00:31:17.080
I don't want to be part of
your medical association.

00:31:17.080 --> 00:31:18.590
And they said, cool.

00:31:18.590 --> 00:31:20.640
Showed him the door.

00:31:20.640 --> 00:31:24.550
That medical doctor's
name was John Snow.

00:31:24.550 --> 00:31:26.090
No, not that John Snow.

00:31:26.090 --> 00:31:28.395
[LAUGHTER]

00:31:30.430 --> 00:31:33.110
That John Snow.

00:31:33.110 --> 00:31:37.820
John Snow hits the
streets and becomes

00:31:37.820 --> 00:31:42.320
an ethnographer of the
community he aims to serve.

00:31:42.320 --> 00:31:44.630
Study after study for
the last four decades

00:31:44.630 --> 00:31:48.620
suggests that the most
successful educators in service

00:31:48.620 --> 00:31:50.660
of the nation's most
vulnerable youth

00:31:50.660 --> 00:31:53.840
are first and
foremost ethnographers

00:31:53.840 --> 00:31:56.150
of the communities
that they serve.

00:31:56.150 --> 00:32:00.290
They are on the streets
when the sun go down.

00:32:00.290 --> 00:32:02.920
They're on the streets
on the weekends.

00:32:02.920 --> 00:32:04.240
They're in the homes.

00:32:04.240 --> 00:32:08.330
They're in the lives of the
people they aim to serve.

00:32:08.330 --> 00:32:13.530
And they're students of those
families in those communities.

00:32:13.530 --> 00:32:17.340
They're researchers,
just like John Snow.

00:32:17.340 --> 00:32:21.880
John Snow said, we don't
have the right data.

00:32:21.880 --> 00:32:25.270
I've got to get better data.

00:32:25.270 --> 00:32:26.990
So he starts
interviewing everybody

00:32:26.990 --> 00:32:31.200
that he can that had cholera,
and everybody that he could

00:32:31.200 --> 00:32:33.910
that didn't have cholera,
and he collects data.

00:32:33.910 --> 00:32:38.550
And what John Snow found in his
data is a researcher's dream.

00:32:38.550 --> 00:32:40.920
He found a perfect binary.

00:32:40.920 --> 00:32:43.450
He found causal.

00:32:43.450 --> 00:32:46.570
What John Snow found is
that every single person

00:32:46.570 --> 00:32:50.810
in London that had cholera
drank from that water fountain.

00:32:50.810 --> 00:32:54.810
And every single person
that didn't, didn't.

00:32:54.810 --> 00:32:59.202
So John Snow got a saw,
and he cut off the handle,

00:32:59.202 --> 00:33:02.480
and cholera stopped.

00:33:02.480 --> 00:33:05.250
London saved.

00:33:05.250 --> 00:33:11.370
Cut off the handle of an
equal education system.

00:33:11.370 --> 00:33:14.430
That pump is poison.

00:33:14.430 --> 00:33:21.000
It has created one of the most
radically unequal democracies

00:33:21.000 --> 00:33:23.820
that we've ever seen.

00:33:23.820 --> 00:33:26.110
Pivot to equity.

00:33:26.110 --> 00:33:30.360
The equity conversation
means that if you're hungry,

00:33:30.360 --> 00:33:32.390
you get food.

00:33:32.390 --> 00:33:35.245
If you're thirsty,
you get water.

00:33:35.245 --> 00:33:37.120
If you're hella thirsty,
you get hella water.

00:33:37.120 --> 00:33:40.660
[LAUGHTER]

00:33:40.660 --> 00:33:48.130
In an equity paradigm, you get
what you need when you need it.

00:33:48.130 --> 00:33:55.330
This is the big commitment
for the pivot to equity.

00:33:55.330 --> 00:33:57.781
The mistake in Brown, 1954--

00:33:57.781 --> 00:33:59.530
a lot of folks don't
know there's actually

00:33:59.530 --> 00:34:00.580
two Brown decisions.

00:34:00.580 --> 00:34:02.740
There's Brown v. Board (1)
and Brown v. Board (2).

00:34:02.740 --> 00:34:06.990
Why did we have to
re-legislate the legislation?

00:34:06.990 --> 00:34:09.190
Why did we need a
second Brown decision?

00:34:09.190 --> 00:34:14.150
Why did the court revisit
its first decision?

00:34:14.150 --> 00:34:16.400
Because we weren't
making any progress.

00:34:16.400 --> 00:34:20.130
They said, what the
hell's going on?

00:34:20.130 --> 00:34:22.679
We legislated racial
desegregation.

00:34:22.679 --> 00:34:23.610
It's not happening.

00:34:23.610 --> 00:34:24.690
What is going on?

00:34:24.690 --> 00:34:27.687
And they went back and they
looked at their decision.

00:34:27.687 --> 00:34:29.520
And what they found is
that in the decision,

00:34:29.520 --> 00:34:34.130
they didn't say when.

00:34:34.130 --> 00:34:37.230
They just said, we will do this.

00:34:37.230 --> 00:34:40.770
So Brown v. Board (2) produces
perhaps the most famous line

00:34:40.770 --> 00:34:42.389
in the Brown decision.

00:34:42.389 --> 00:34:45.170
"With all deliberate speed."

00:34:45.170 --> 00:34:45.670
When?

00:34:45.670 --> 00:34:47.139
"With all deliberate speed."

00:34:47.139 --> 00:34:51.310
Well, apparently, that
means backwards first.

00:34:51.310 --> 00:34:53.500
If you're going
to do equity, make

00:34:53.500 --> 00:34:57.620
sure you say when
you're going to do it.

00:34:57.620 --> 00:35:02.320
By when will that group of kids
have a different experience

00:35:02.320 --> 00:35:05.980
in your classroom, in your
school, in your programs,

00:35:05.980 --> 00:35:06.790
in your community?

00:35:06.790 --> 00:35:10.090
Because if you don't say
when, then you'll just wring

00:35:10.090 --> 00:35:12.640
your hands when you don't.

00:35:12.640 --> 00:35:14.980
Because you're not on
the hook for anything.

00:35:14.980 --> 00:35:17.440
You'll talk about how
hard you're trying.

00:35:17.440 --> 00:35:19.030
We tried this, we tried that.

00:35:19.030 --> 00:35:20.920
We hired this person,
we hired that person.

00:35:20.920 --> 00:35:22.850
No results.

00:35:22.850 --> 00:35:26.590
Very same thing we find
intolerable with our children.

00:35:26.590 --> 00:35:28.150
You must produce results.

00:35:28.150 --> 00:35:31.780
We model that for them
as adults in schools.

00:35:31.780 --> 00:35:34.499
We hand-wring.

00:35:34.499 --> 00:35:36.040
But you put yourself
on the hook when

00:35:36.040 --> 00:35:37.915
you say when you're
going to do these things.

00:35:37.915 --> 00:35:39.640
By this date, we
will have this done.

00:35:39.640 --> 00:35:42.850
By this date, this data
will look this way.

00:35:42.850 --> 00:35:44.830
And you may miss the mark.

00:35:44.830 --> 00:35:48.200
But now it's power
that's on the hook.

00:35:48.200 --> 00:35:50.830
It's power that's accountable.

00:35:50.830 --> 00:35:56.020
And it's power that's often the
least accountable for change.

00:35:56.020 --> 00:35:57.460
So put yourselves on the hook.

00:35:57.460 --> 00:36:00.160
Then you earn the
right to really push

00:36:00.160 --> 00:36:04.290
children and families
to come along with us.

00:36:04.290 --> 00:36:08.190
Now this is not anything
particularly new.

00:36:10.770 --> 00:36:16.150
Maslow, 1943.

00:36:16.150 --> 00:36:18.850
1943.

00:36:18.850 --> 00:36:22.950
Of all the schools
that are in this room,

00:36:22.950 --> 00:36:27.750
I would stake my career on
this statement, that there

00:36:27.750 --> 00:36:33.260
is nothing being used in your
schools that has the research

00:36:33.260 --> 00:36:35.510
base of Maslow.

00:36:35.510 --> 00:36:40.430
Seven-plus decades
cross-disciplinary.

00:36:40.430 --> 00:36:44.060
Public health, social
epidemiology, neuroscience,

00:36:44.060 --> 00:36:49.540
the medical field, child
development, psychology all

00:36:49.540 --> 00:36:50.370
agree.

00:36:50.370 --> 00:36:51.250
Yep.

00:36:51.250 --> 00:36:52.176
He's right.

00:36:55.420 --> 00:36:59.770
So if your school is both
data-driven and research-based,

00:36:59.770 --> 00:37:01.350
start with Maslow.

00:37:01.350 --> 00:37:03.490
Every time you get
stuck with a kid,

00:37:03.490 --> 00:37:07.120
every time you get stuck with
a family, start with Maslow.

00:37:07.120 --> 00:37:08.500
Start at the base.

00:37:08.500 --> 00:37:12.010
Food, clothing, shelter,
safety, basic needs.

00:37:12.010 --> 00:37:16.330
We know from all of those
fields that if a kid shows up

00:37:16.330 --> 00:37:18.600
hungry, what can't they do?

00:37:18.600 --> 00:37:19.480
AUDIENCE: Learn.

00:37:19.480 --> 00:37:20.479
JEFF DUNCAN-ANDRADE: OK?

00:37:20.479 --> 00:37:22.600
They can't engage.

00:37:22.600 --> 00:37:26.770
They can't engage around
anything but their hunger.

00:37:26.770 --> 00:37:29.380
If a kid feels unsafe--

00:37:29.380 --> 00:37:31.974
I see all these safety
plans for schools,

00:37:31.974 --> 00:37:33.640
and the only thing
they're talking about

00:37:33.640 --> 00:37:36.100
is physical safety.

00:37:36.100 --> 00:37:37.490
Physical safety.

00:37:37.490 --> 00:37:41.050
And what that presumes is that
all the other layers of safety

00:37:41.050 --> 00:37:45.050
are de facto, and they're
not for kids of color.

00:37:45.050 --> 00:37:47.390
They're not for
language learners.

00:37:47.390 --> 00:37:49.240
They're not for girls.

00:37:49.240 --> 00:37:52.600
They're not for your
lesbian, gay, trans kids.

00:37:52.600 --> 00:37:53.340
They're not.

00:37:53.340 --> 00:37:57.660
Those safeties, those identity
safeties are not de facto.

00:37:57.660 --> 00:37:59.960
So physical safety,
super important,

00:37:59.960 --> 00:38:01.900
but so is identity safety.

00:38:01.900 --> 00:38:04.420
Are the children safe
to show up and be

00:38:04.420 --> 00:38:11.020
who they really are culturally,
linguistically, sexually?

00:38:11.020 --> 00:38:14.020
Because if they're not,
what can't they do?

00:38:14.020 --> 00:38:14.990
Can't learn.

00:38:14.990 --> 00:38:17.410
If you're unsafe, you can't--

00:38:17.410 --> 00:38:19.340
we know this.

00:38:19.340 --> 00:38:22.280
There is no debate
in the research

00:38:22.280 --> 00:38:24.410
field about these things.

00:38:24.410 --> 00:38:27.380
And yet the
transference to schools

00:38:27.380 --> 00:38:30.650
has not happened in a way
that is true and authentic

00:38:30.650 --> 00:38:34.700
and embedded wall to wall,
tip to finish, edge to edge.

00:38:34.700 --> 00:38:36.380
Because we push off
of this and we get

00:38:36.380 --> 00:38:39.260
sucked into Pearson and
Houghton Mifflin and Common

00:38:39.260 --> 00:38:44.441
Core, when this is Common Core.

00:38:44.441 --> 00:38:46.820
And you know who knows this?

00:38:46.820 --> 00:38:49.590
Wealthy schools.

00:38:49.590 --> 00:38:51.590
This is where they always start.

00:38:51.590 --> 00:38:53.210
Are kids safe?

00:38:53.210 --> 00:38:55.310
Are they clothed and fed?

00:38:55.310 --> 00:38:58.750
Do they have a sense
of love and belonging?

00:38:58.750 --> 00:39:01.390
Do they feel good
about themselves?

00:39:01.390 --> 00:39:03.100
Basic stuff.

00:39:03.100 --> 00:39:06.820
And when the basics are
met, it is a biological fact

00:39:06.820 --> 00:39:09.790
that the human being
will self-actualize.

00:39:09.790 --> 00:39:12.570
If you have children
in your schools,

00:39:12.570 --> 00:39:15.310
if you have teachers
in your schools

00:39:15.310 --> 00:39:18.220
that are not
self-actualizing, we

00:39:18.220 --> 00:39:21.070
are crystal clear in
the research about why.

00:39:21.070 --> 00:39:26.390
Something underneath it is
unstable or under attack.

00:39:26.390 --> 00:39:29.770
It has nothing to do with
whether the kid's black, brown,

00:39:29.770 --> 00:39:34.350
purple, pink, tall,
short, fast, or slow.

00:39:34.350 --> 00:39:38.400
What we know in the research
is that any human being who

00:39:38.400 --> 00:39:41.370
has their basic
needs under attack

00:39:41.370 --> 00:39:44.160
will not consistently
self-actualize.

00:39:44.160 --> 00:39:46.140
What that means is this.

00:39:46.140 --> 00:39:48.930
No child that you
serve is broken,

00:39:48.930 --> 00:39:52.260
so don't try to fix them.

00:39:52.260 --> 00:39:53.830
We're spending all
this time trying

00:39:53.830 --> 00:39:55.240
to fix stuff that ain't broke.

00:39:55.240 --> 00:39:57.502
Didn't your mama ever tell
you if it ain't broke--

00:39:57.502 --> 00:39:58.460
AUDIENCE: Don't fix it.

00:39:58.460 --> 00:39:59.270
JEFF DUNCAN-ANDRADE:
Don't fix it.

00:39:59.270 --> 00:40:00.337
Don't fix these kids.

00:40:00.337 --> 00:40:01.670
There's nothing wrong with them.

00:40:01.670 --> 00:40:03.730
There's something wrong
with this society.

00:40:03.730 --> 00:40:06.490
There's something wrong with the
systems we're putting them in.

00:40:06.490 --> 00:40:08.410
That's what has to be fixed.

00:40:08.410 --> 00:40:13.360
So when a kid is off the
mark, become a bulldozer.

00:40:13.360 --> 00:40:16.720
What we know in the research
is the most effective teachers

00:40:16.720 --> 00:40:19.870
of vulnerable youth
are bulldozers.

00:40:19.870 --> 00:40:23.710
And what I mean is that they
figure out what's in the way,

00:40:23.710 --> 00:40:26.170
and they clear it
out so that the kid

00:40:26.170 --> 00:40:28.240
can be who they already are.

00:40:28.240 --> 00:40:34.530
Can you see every child that
you serve as GATE, as gifted

00:40:34.530 --> 00:40:35.590
and talented?

00:40:35.590 --> 00:40:36.690
Because just [INAUDIBLE].

00:40:36.690 --> 00:40:38.880
So y'all get GATE
programs in your schools?

00:40:38.880 --> 00:40:41.180
Gifted and talented
programs in your schools?

00:40:41.180 --> 00:40:43.510
OK, just peek this
game for a minute, OK?

00:40:43.510 --> 00:40:50.072
If this table is the GATE
table, then they are what?

00:40:50.072 --> 00:40:52.790
They are gifted and talented.

00:40:52.790 --> 00:40:54.965
Well, what does that
make the rest of y'all?

00:40:54.965 --> 00:40:56.069
[INTERPOSING VOICES]

00:40:56.069 --> 00:40:57.110
JEFF DUNCAN-ANDRADE: Yep.

00:40:57.110 --> 00:40:58.070
OK.

00:40:58.070 --> 00:40:59.420
Every child is GATE.

00:40:59.420 --> 00:41:01.700
Not every child
performs as GATE.

00:41:01.700 --> 00:41:05.120
The question for us as
educators is, why not?

00:41:05.120 --> 00:41:06.710
Why not?

00:41:06.710 --> 00:41:10.370
If talent is equally distributed
throughout the population,

00:41:10.370 --> 00:41:14.240
which is what we absolutely
have landed on in all

00:41:14.240 --> 00:41:17.510
of our research in neuroscience
and biology and biochemistry,

00:41:17.510 --> 00:41:20.940
talent is randomly distributed
throughout the population,

00:41:20.940 --> 00:41:23.740
why isn't success?

00:41:23.740 --> 00:41:26.110
There must be
something systemically

00:41:26.110 --> 00:41:29.080
wrong with the way in
which we cultivate talent,

00:41:29.080 --> 00:41:32.260
and schools are a
major engine in that.

00:41:32.260 --> 00:41:35.770
And the ways in which we try
to cultivate talent oftentimes

00:41:35.770 --> 00:41:38.860
is by fixing kids who don't
fit in in the way that's

00:41:38.860 --> 00:41:41.170
convenient for us
instead of figuring out

00:41:41.170 --> 00:41:42.790
what we need to
clear out of the way

00:41:42.790 --> 00:41:44.620
so the kid can be
who they already are.

00:41:44.620 --> 00:41:49.180
That is the mind shift that we
make when we move to equity.

00:41:49.180 --> 00:41:52.150
Not everybody's going to get
the same thing at the same time.

00:41:52.150 --> 00:41:55.110
You're going to get what
you need when you need it.

00:41:55.110 --> 00:41:57.450
And the most vulnerable
youth are going to need more.

00:41:57.450 --> 00:42:00.230
A lot more.

00:42:00.230 --> 00:42:03.430
This is why Eduardo Galeano
says Western nation states have

00:42:03.430 --> 00:42:05.980
built a world upside down.

00:42:05.980 --> 00:42:09.300
A world upside down is where
those who need the least

00:42:09.300 --> 00:42:12.720
get the most and those who
need the most get the least.

00:42:12.720 --> 00:42:14.490
And that is the
working definition

00:42:14.490 --> 00:42:17.379
of our current society.

00:42:17.379 --> 00:42:18.920
We have to invert
that if we're going

00:42:18.920 --> 00:42:21.170
to be a pluralistic,
multiracial democracy.

00:42:21.170 --> 00:42:24.970
Those who need the most in
your school must get the most.

00:42:24.970 --> 00:42:26.930
And this is going
to be the hard sell.

00:42:26.930 --> 00:42:32.100
Those who need the least
are going to get least.

00:42:32.100 --> 00:42:33.050
That's the hard sell.

00:42:33.050 --> 00:42:35.210
Can you convince
families that have

00:42:35.210 --> 00:42:38.750
the most that it's actually
good for their kid for this kid

00:42:38.750 --> 00:42:41.830
to get more than their kid?

00:42:41.830 --> 00:42:45.130
And in a structured
school where your grade

00:42:45.130 --> 00:42:49.340
has nothing to do with your
grade, that's not possible.

00:42:49.340 --> 00:42:52.490
How do we create a
collectivity community

00:42:52.490 --> 00:42:55.400
that is building our collective
responsibility to one another

00:42:55.400 --> 00:42:57.500
where if you have a whole
hell of a lot of food

00:42:57.500 --> 00:43:02.390
and you ain't got no food, by
definition, you give it up?

00:43:02.390 --> 00:43:05.160
That's a pluralistic,
multiracial democracy.

00:43:05.160 --> 00:43:07.160
That's not what we're
norming in schools.

00:43:07.160 --> 00:43:08.950
Right now, what
we norm in schools

00:43:08.950 --> 00:43:10.880
is if you've got the
answer to the test

00:43:10.880 --> 00:43:13.820
and she don't and you give
them to her, you're a--

00:43:13.820 --> 00:43:14.570
AUDIENCE: Cheater.

00:43:14.570 --> 00:43:16.460
JEFF DUNCAN-ANDRADE: Cheater.

00:43:16.460 --> 00:43:19.040
Beginning in
kindergarten, we norm it.

00:43:19.040 --> 00:43:21.890
You share your knowledge,
you share your access

00:43:21.890 --> 00:43:25.820
to power and opportunity,
you're a cheater.

00:43:25.820 --> 00:43:28.070
It's actually bad for her.

00:43:28.070 --> 00:43:31.800
She got to pull herself
up by her boot straps.

00:43:31.800 --> 00:43:34.260
Then you'll really learn
the positive of work ethic

00:43:34.260 --> 00:43:38.290
and how to-- we're not
building collectivity.

00:43:38.290 --> 00:43:41.210
And the research
community is particularly

00:43:41.210 --> 00:43:43.630
concerned about this
because of what's

00:43:43.630 --> 00:43:46.610
showing up in health
and wellness data

00:43:46.610 --> 00:43:48.590
like the Peace Index.

00:43:48.590 --> 00:43:50.850
We don't have a peaceful
society, and schools

00:43:50.850 --> 00:43:54.350
and norming that just with
basic, structural, day-to-day

00:43:54.350 --> 00:43:57.000
functioning.

00:43:57.000 --> 00:44:00.720
Now I must say about Maslow,
what Maslow said himself

00:44:00.720 --> 00:44:03.330
that the rest of the
nation continually ignores

00:44:03.330 --> 00:44:04.770
when they talk about his work.

00:44:04.770 --> 00:44:07.500
That Maslow did not come up
with the hierarchy of needs.

00:44:07.500 --> 00:44:09.540
Maslow appropriated it.

00:44:09.540 --> 00:44:11.800
Maslow took the concept
of the hierarchy of needs

00:44:11.800 --> 00:44:14.620
from the Blackfoot
people, Blackfoot nation.

00:44:14.620 --> 00:44:18.510
Breath of life is what we call
it in indigenous communities.

00:44:18.510 --> 00:44:24.540
It's an inverted triangle where
self-actualization actually

00:44:24.540 --> 00:44:29.370
sits on the bottom, and the
ultimate goal, the highest form

00:44:29.370 --> 00:44:33.880
of community and collectivity
is cultural perpetuation,

00:44:33.880 --> 00:44:35.610
the passing along.

00:44:35.610 --> 00:44:39.960
Culture, identity,
language, traditions.

00:44:39.960 --> 00:44:43.260
That's a sustainable
nation state.

00:44:43.260 --> 00:44:47.351
Because now you must connect
with people in your community

00:44:47.351 --> 00:44:47.850
to do that.

00:44:47.850 --> 00:44:50.840
You cannot do that alone.

00:44:50.840 --> 00:44:52.490
Maslow inverts the paradigm.

00:44:52.490 --> 00:44:56.690
Says, yes, that that
is the healthy society.

00:44:56.690 --> 00:44:59.640
But we are so far
from that-- in 1943,

00:44:59.640 --> 00:45:03.380
we are so far from that in this
nation that we actually have

00:45:03.380 --> 00:45:05.210
to start with basic--

00:45:05.210 --> 00:45:08.270
we actually have built
a society that we

00:45:08.270 --> 00:45:12.290
have to say you have to
feed, clothe, shelter,

00:45:12.290 --> 00:45:14.370
and protect children.

00:45:14.370 --> 00:45:17.050
That's a messed up
society where you actually

00:45:17.050 --> 00:45:20.200
have to say those words,
but that's where we're at.

00:45:20.200 --> 00:45:23.650
Maslow says that very clearly
in his early work, right?

00:45:23.650 --> 00:45:26.110
He says that the
Blackfoot people have

00:45:26.110 --> 00:45:30.610
built a healthy,
sustainable society,

00:45:30.610 --> 00:45:33.620
and we're headed in
the wrong direction.

00:45:33.620 --> 00:45:36.730
So we've got to
reset and say first,

00:45:36.730 --> 00:45:40.480
all children must have food,
clothing, shelter, safety.

00:45:40.480 --> 00:45:41.530
Basic needs.

00:45:41.530 --> 00:45:43.870
Everybody has to have those met.

00:45:43.870 --> 00:45:46.870
Everybody has to have a
sense of love and belonging.

00:45:46.870 --> 00:45:50.290
Everybody has to have a sense
of self-love, self-esteem

00:45:50.290 --> 00:45:56.810
in order for us to then talk
about collective culture.

00:45:56.810 --> 00:46:00.530
It's important that
that is re-narrated

00:46:00.530 --> 00:46:04.250
as we talk about Maslow, that
this is not a Western idea.

00:46:04.250 --> 00:46:07.910
It's an indigenous idea
that has been largely

00:46:07.910 --> 00:46:10.460
attributed to
Western science when

00:46:10.460 --> 00:46:15.367
in fact, Western science got
the idea from indigenous people.

00:46:15.367 --> 00:46:17.450
Now the second part of the
talk, what I want to do

00:46:17.450 --> 00:46:20.400
is armor you up to
go do this work.

00:46:20.400 --> 00:46:23.540
I want you to know that
the research is completely

00:46:23.540 --> 00:46:25.550
on your side.

00:46:25.550 --> 00:46:27.230
In the research
community, we don't even

00:46:27.230 --> 00:46:29.960
debate this stuff anymore.

00:46:29.960 --> 00:46:34.120
We're just trying to
figure out how to go from--

00:46:34.120 --> 00:46:35.890
how to close the
knowing-doing gap.

00:46:35.890 --> 00:46:36.760
Because we know.

00:46:36.760 --> 00:46:41.320
We actually have really, really
conclusive, good research,

00:46:41.320 --> 00:46:44.530
but we're not doing
it on the ground.

00:46:44.530 --> 00:46:48.650
That's the gap we've got to
close in this generation.

00:46:48.650 --> 00:46:52.410
How do we do what we know
we're supposed to do?

00:46:52.410 --> 00:46:55.350
What we find in the research is
the most successful educators

00:46:55.350 --> 00:46:57.540
focus on those three
things that I called out

00:46:57.540 --> 00:46:58.890
around self-actualization.

00:46:58.890 --> 00:47:01.920
Relationships, relevance,
and responsibility.

00:47:01.920 --> 00:47:05.730
When the policy rain comes,
they've got an umbrella,

00:47:05.730 --> 00:47:08.795
and that umbrella is
called good teaching.

00:47:08.795 --> 00:47:10.170
They just throw
that umbrella up,

00:47:10.170 --> 00:47:13.520
and they know at the end of the
day, relationships, relevance,

00:47:13.520 --> 00:47:16.380
responsibility, and my
kids are going to be fine.

00:47:16.380 --> 00:47:17.852
My classroom's going to be fine.

00:47:17.852 --> 00:47:19.060
My school's going to be fine.

00:47:19.060 --> 00:47:21.435
I'm not going to get caught
up in latest, greatest ideas.

00:47:21.435 --> 00:47:24.060
Relevance-- excuse me,
relationships, relevance,

00:47:24.060 --> 00:47:25.020
responsibility.

00:47:25.020 --> 00:47:27.360
And the research bears
this out time and time

00:47:27.360 --> 00:47:28.937
again for four-plus decades.

00:47:28.937 --> 00:47:31.020
So I'm going to armor you
up with some of the best

00:47:31.020 --> 00:47:32.970
research we have
so you don't even

00:47:32.970 --> 00:47:36.930
have to have the debate,
because it's a false debate.

00:47:36.930 --> 00:47:38.520
It's a false debate.

00:47:38.520 --> 00:47:40.830
It's a debate over
ideology instead

00:47:40.830 --> 00:47:42.090
of what's good for kids.

00:47:42.090 --> 00:47:45.330
And any time you get into
an ideological debate

00:47:45.330 --> 00:47:51.140
with people who aren't
moral, it ends in stalemate.

00:47:51.140 --> 00:47:53.330
And our goal with the
research and our practice

00:47:53.330 --> 00:47:56.600
is to end the debate.

00:47:56.600 --> 00:47:59.630
Because we know what works,
we know how it works,

00:47:59.630 --> 00:48:01.880
and we know why it works,
and I want everybody

00:48:01.880 --> 00:48:05.120
leaving here armored
up with the best

00:48:05.120 --> 00:48:10.790
research we have in the nation
for why those things are true

00:48:10.790 --> 00:48:14.670
and with an image burned in your
mind about what it looks like.

00:48:14.670 --> 00:48:16.400
So for each of these
three, I'm going

00:48:16.400 --> 00:48:20.270
to give you a live look
into a classroom or a school

00:48:20.270 --> 00:48:23.660
that we've worked with that are
doing this as well or better

00:48:23.660 --> 00:48:26.240
than anybody else on the
planet, because two of them

00:48:26.240 --> 00:48:29.430
are actually going
to be international.

00:48:29.430 --> 00:48:32.750
So we start with relationships,
because at the end

00:48:32.750 --> 00:48:36.069
of the day, if you've taught
for a day, you know this.

00:48:36.069 --> 00:48:38.110
The end of the day, teaching
and learning always,

00:48:38.110 --> 00:48:40.330
always, always boils
down to relationships.

00:48:40.330 --> 00:48:42.540
We keep trying to
change the curriculum,

00:48:42.540 --> 00:48:44.470
but we're not changing
relationships.

00:48:44.470 --> 00:48:46.450
Curriculum won't save you.

00:48:46.450 --> 00:48:50.800
Curriculum matters, but
curriculum won't save you.

00:48:50.800 --> 00:48:52.300
At the end of day,
it's going to be,

00:48:52.300 --> 00:48:53.760
can we build better
relationships

00:48:53.760 --> 00:48:56.260
with the kids and the families
that feel really disconnected

00:48:56.260 --> 00:48:57.330
from our institutions?

00:48:57.330 --> 00:49:00.810
So Herb Kohl who is
not far from here,

00:49:00.810 --> 00:49:04.910
a longtime faculty member at
the University of San Francisco,

00:49:04.910 --> 00:49:06.660
wrote this book, "I
Won't Learn From You."

00:49:06.660 --> 00:49:08.451
And it's one of my
all-time favorite books,

00:49:08.451 --> 00:49:10.350
because it's one of
the only studies--

00:49:10.350 --> 00:49:15.030
comprehensive studies we
have of students that fail,

00:49:15.030 --> 00:49:20.560
and seeing their failure as
conscious and deliberate.

00:49:20.560 --> 00:49:21.520
Yeah.

00:49:21.520 --> 00:49:24.520
This flipped my wig, right?

00:49:24.520 --> 00:49:26.110
Because Herb says,
how many of you

00:49:26.110 --> 00:49:28.094
have kids that
show up to class--

00:49:28.094 --> 00:49:30.010
you don't even know what
I'm going to ask yet.

00:49:30.010 --> 00:49:30.560
You raise--

00:49:30.560 --> 00:49:32.010
[LAUGHTER]

00:49:32.509 --> 00:49:33.550
Yeah, how many have kids?

00:49:33.550 --> 00:49:34.633
How many of you have kids?

00:49:34.633 --> 00:49:35.395
Just show a hands.

00:49:35.395 --> 00:49:35.710
All right.

00:49:35.710 --> 00:49:36.210
Yeah.

00:49:36.210 --> 00:49:37.870
All the parents in the room, OK?

00:49:37.870 --> 00:49:38.830
Happy Parents Day.

00:49:38.830 --> 00:49:39.445
OK.

00:49:39.445 --> 00:49:43.607
So how many of you have
kids, students, youth--

00:49:43.607 --> 00:49:45.190
OK, sorry, I asked
the wrong question.

00:49:45.190 --> 00:49:47.110
It's always on me.

00:49:47.110 --> 00:49:52.439
That show up to class,
like damn near every day,

00:49:52.439 --> 00:49:54.730
and then you get to marking
period, you get to grading,

00:49:54.730 --> 00:49:56.350
and you look, and they've
got straight-up zeros

00:49:56.350 --> 00:49:56.680
in the grade book.

00:49:56.680 --> 00:49:58.120
How many of you have that kid?

00:49:58.120 --> 00:50:00.260
OK?

00:50:00.260 --> 00:50:04.386
Herb Kohl says, that's you're
most committed student.

00:50:04.386 --> 00:50:06.378
[LAUGHTER]

00:50:06.378 --> 00:50:08.370
That's some hard shit to do.

00:50:08.370 --> 00:50:10.870
[LAUGHTER]

00:50:10.870 --> 00:50:13.878
Show up every day
and do nothing.

00:50:13.878 --> 00:50:16.626
[LAUGHTER]

00:50:16.626 --> 00:50:18.007
Try that one time.

00:50:18.007 --> 00:50:19.340
How many principals in the room?

00:50:19.340 --> 00:50:19.860
Principals?

00:50:19.860 --> 00:50:20.290
OK.

00:50:20.290 --> 00:50:20.450
OK.

00:50:20.450 --> 00:50:21.670
I'm going to do you
dirty right now.

00:50:21.670 --> 00:50:22.170
OK.

00:50:22.170 --> 00:50:22.730
[LAUGHTER]

00:50:22.730 --> 00:50:24.590
So for all the staff
members in the room,

00:50:24.590 --> 00:50:26.240
OK, here's what
I want you to do.

00:50:26.240 --> 00:50:26.740
All right?

00:50:26.740 --> 00:50:30.360
The next time you have
to go to a staff meeting

00:50:30.360 --> 00:50:34.672
or PD led by your principal,
here's your goal, all right?

00:50:34.672 --> 00:50:35.380
Here's your goal.

00:50:35.380 --> 00:50:38.710
I'm giving a very
clear, defined goal.

00:50:38.710 --> 00:50:39.970
Learn nothing.

00:50:39.970 --> 00:50:41.436
[LAUGHTER]

00:50:41.436 --> 00:50:42.560
Some of you are like, shit.

00:50:42.560 --> 00:50:43.518
That's every damn time.

00:50:43.518 --> 00:50:46.330
[LAUGHTER]

00:50:46.330 --> 00:50:49.540
Learn nothing, OK?

00:50:49.540 --> 00:50:53.870
Herb Kohl called it
willed not learning.

00:50:53.870 --> 00:50:56.360
He says it takes a
conscious effort.

00:50:56.360 --> 00:51:01.470
You must will yourself to
sit in school and not learn.

00:51:01.470 --> 00:51:03.080
Hey And he came
to understand this

00:51:03.080 --> 00:51:06.930
by interviewing the least
successful students.

00:51:06.930 --> 00:51:10.225
And what he found is they're
excellent at what they're

00:51:10.225 --> 00:51:12.350
attempting to do, and what
they're attempting to do

00:51:12.350 --> 00:51:16.000
is protect themselves from us.

00:51:16.000 --> 00:51:18.140
And so they come
to school every day

00:51:18.140 --> 00:51:21.000
because the other option
is going to lockup.

00:51:21.000 --> 00:51:23.970
So they come to school every
day with a conscious commitment

00:51:23.970 --> 00:51:26.700
that, I won't learn from you.

00:51:26.700 --> 00:51:30.120
And he's like, that
makes no sense to me.

00:51:30.120 --> 00:51:33.600
It's brilliant, but it
makes no sense to me.

00:51:33.600 --> 00:51:35.910
And he said-- and
one kid says to him,

00:51:35.910 --> 00:51:38.100
he says, I don't
care what you know

00:51:38.100 --> 00:51:43.050
until I know that you care, and
I know these people don't care.

00:51:43.050 --> 00:51:46.640
And it doesn't matter
if we think we care.

00:51:46.640 --> 00:51:48.590
Care is not about
what you think.

00:51:48.590 --> 00:51:51.140
It's about whether or not
the recipient of your care

00:51:51.140 --> 00:51:52.460
feels cared about.

00:51:52.460 --> 00:51:54.110
And we've got so
many kids in schools

00:51:54.110 --> 00:51:55.880
that don't feel cared about.

00:51:55.880 --> 00:51:57.260
That's the starting point.

00:51:57.260 --> 00:51:58.430
Basic needs.

00:51:58.430 --> 00:52:02.510
Food, clothing, shelter, safety.

00:52:02.510 --> 00:52:04.580
Love and belonging.

00:52:04.580 --> 00:52:08.420
Interview your least
successful students.

00:52:08.420 --> 00:52:11.210
Try to understand
that they are actually

00:52:11.210 --> 00:52:13.525
some of your most
successful students,

00:52:13.525 --> 00:52:15.650
because they're achieving
exactly what they set out

00:52:15.650 --> 00:52:17.680
to achieve.

00:52:17.680 --> 00:52:19.970
If we don't understand
that, we can't pivot them

00:52:19.970 --> 00:52:21.070
in another direction.

00:52:21.070 --> 00:52:23.090
There's wonderful
research on this.

00:52:23.090 --> 00:52:25.970
Herb Kohl's a great
starting point.

00:52:25.970 --> 00:52:27.970
But the research goes
on and on and on.

00:52:27.970 --> 00:52:30.736
This afternoon, I'm going
to be down at Stanford

00:52:30.736 --> 00:52:32.110
doing some work
with these folks.

00:52:32.110 --> 00:52:33.594
Robert Sapolsky.

00:52:33.594 --> 00:52:35.135
He just had a great
interview on NPR.

00:52:35.135 --> 00:52:38.020
If you're an NPR fan, you can
hear some of his latest work.

00:52:38.020 --> 00:52:41.290
Robert Sapolsky is considered
the world's leading researcher

00:52:41.290 --> 00:52:43.364
on stress.

00:52:43.364 --> 00:52:45.030
His book, "Why Zebras
Don't get Ulcers,"

00:52:45.030 --> 00:52:48.270
is mandatory reading in
every single medical field.

00:52:48.270 --> 00:52:51.720
Social epidemiology, public
health, neuroscience, medicine.

00:52:51.720 --> 00:52:53.730
Everybody has to read Sapolsky.

00:52:53.730 --> 00:52:56.980
I find almost no teachers
have ever read it,

00:52:56.980 --> 00:52:59.590
and I actually don't
recommend that you do, OK?

00:52:59.590 --> 00:53:03.238
Because this book is, like,
600 pages in six-point font.

00:53:03.238 --> 00:53:04.990
[LAUGHTER]

00:53:04.990 --> 00:53:10.450
However, there is a
wonderful National Geographic

00:53:10.450 --> 00:53:13.420
30-minute documentary
film on his work

00:53:13.420 --> 00:53:15.970
that is fantastic that
you can get on YouTube.

00:53:15.970 --> 00:53:18.320
OK, it's a great PD.

00:53:18.320 --> 00:53:20.260
It's called "Stress,"
the silent killer.

00:53:23.190 --> 00:53:23.690
OK.

00:53:27.620 --> 00:53:28.882
Brene Brown.

00:53:28.882 --> 00:53:30.590
Many people are familiar
with Brene Brown

00:53:30.590 --> 00:53:33.230
because her TED Talk blew up.

00:53:33.230 --> 00:53:35.227
A lot of folks don't know
that Brene Brown also

00:53:35.227 --> 00:53:37.310
wrote a "New York Times"
bestseller called "Daring

00:53:37.310 --> 00:53:41.540
Greatly" where she expands
and expounds upon what

00:53:41.540 --> 00:53:42.780
you hear in her TED Talk.

00:53:42.780 --> 00:53:47.180
So if you-- the TED Talk's a
great primer for vulnerability

00:53:47.180 --> 00:53:51.420
and understanding the difference
between sympathy and empathy.

00:53:51.420 --> 00:53:53.830
And what we see happening
a lot in schools

00:53:53.830 --> 00:53:56.200
in the relationships
with vulnerable youth

00:53:56.200 --> 00:53:58.640
is sympathetic relationships.

00:53:58.640 --> 00:54:02.950
So what is a sympathetic
relationship?

00:54:02.950 --> 00:54:04.820
AUDIENCE: When you
feel sorry for them.

00:54:04.820 --> 00:54:05.400
JEFF DUNCAN-ANDRADE: Right.

00:54:05.400 --> 00:54:05.899
OK?

00:54:05.899 --> 00:54:06.970
You feel sorry for them.

00:54:06.970 --> 00:54:09.850
Does anybody know what
happens to you biochemically

00:54:09.850 --> 00:54:13.510
and neurologically when you
have a sympathetic connection

00:54:13.510 --> 00:54:15.900
with somebody?

00:54:15.900 --> 00:54:18.980
What actually
happens inside you?

00:54:18.980 --> 00:54:20.840
Anybody know?

00:54:20.840 --> 00:54:23.070
That's what you want to
start understanding better.

00:54:23.070 --> 00:54:25.820
Don't understand the
external portrayal.

00:54:25.820 --> 00:54:28.240
Understand what's
going on inside.

00:54:28.240 --> 00:54:30.150
Because if you change
what's going on inside,

00:54:30.150 --> 00:54:32.720
you're going change
what's coming out, OK?

00:54:32.720 --> 00:54:35.170
So what's going on inside
your body if I have--

00:54:35.170 --> 00:54:37.970
if I have a sympathetic
connection to her,

00:54:37.970 --> 00:54:39.174
I feel sorry for you--

00:54:39.174 --> 00:54:40.090
I don't know why yet--

00:54:42.680 --> 00:54:47.108
what's going on in my
brain and my biochemistry?

00:54:47.108 --> 00:54:48.494
AUDIENCE: I mean,
are you at all?

00:54:48.494 --> 00:54:50.810
JEFF DUNCAN-ANDRADE: Nothing.

00:54:50.810 --> 00:54:52.170
Nothing.

00:54:52.170 --> 00:54:53.910
No shifts.

00:54:53.910 --> 00:54:57.304
What's going on in
her biochemistry?

00:54:57.304 --> 00:54:59.288
Nothing.

00:54:59.288 --> 00:55:03.270
It's a false connection.

00:55:03.270 --> 00:55:05.654
I'm glad I'm not you.

00:55:05.654 --> 00:55:06.630
Right?

00:55:06.630 --> 00:55:08.717
That's sympathy.

00:55:08.717 --> 00:55:11.482
What's empathy?

00:55:11.482 --> 00:55:13.607
AUDIENCE: Putting yourself
in someone else's shoes.

00:55:13.607 --> 00:55:14.096
JEFF DUNCAN-ANDRADE: Huh?

00:55:14.096 --> 00:55:14.590
AUDIENCE: Putting yourself--

00:55:14.590 --> 00:55:15.250
JEFF DUNCAN-ANDRADE:
Putting yourself

00:55:15.250 --> 00:55:16.960
in someone else's shoes.

00:55:16.960 --> 00:55:19.177
How many have young people
that say, I feel you?

00:55:19.177 --> 00:55:20.385
(DEEP VOICE) I feel you, dog.

00:55:20.385 --> 00:55:20.940
I feel you.

00:55:20.940 --> 00:55:22.240
[LAUGHTER]

00:55:22.240 --> 00:55:24.670
They're literally
expressing empathy.

00:55:24.670 --> 00:55:26.860
Empathy is, I feel you.

00:55:26.860 --> 00:55:29.620
If I have an empathetic
connection to her,

00:55:29.620 --> 00:55:35.590
what happens to my neural
pathways and my biochemistry?

00:55:35.590 --> 00:55:37.680
Exploding.

00:55:37.680 --> 00:55:41.110
What happens to
her neurochemistry?

00:55:41.110 --> 00:55:43.920
Exploding, because
it's connection.

00:55:43.920 --> 00:55:44.940
I feel you.

00:55:44.940 --> 00:55:47.380
I literally feel your pain.

00:55:47.380 --> 00:55:49.440
I feel your joy.

00:55:49.440 --> 00:55:52.740
That connectedness is
what Brene Brown's work

00:55:52.740 --> 00:55:54.450
has helped us understand.

00:55:54.450 --> 00:55:58.400
The false connection of
sympathy and the vulnerability

00:55:58.400 --> 00:56:01.860
that is required to make
an empathic connection.

00:56:01.860 --> 00:56:04.200
And the bioregistry
that we see when

00:56:04.200 --> 00:56:08.770
you make an empathic
connection is off the charts.

00:56:08.770 --> 00:56:10.500
And what's most
compelling about what

00:56:10.500 --> 00:56:12.390
we find that's
happening in the body

00:56:12.390 --> 00:56:14.250
when you have an
empathic connection

00:56:14.250 --> 00:56:20.430
is your massive release of
oxytocin, the happy chemical.

00:56:20.430 --> 00:56:24.570
It is so good for your body
to make empathic connections,

00:56:24.570 --> 00:56:27.900
and it's so good
for your body too.

00:56:27.900 --> 00:56:31.140
It's really, really
good for your teachers

00:56:31.140 --> 00:56:35.250
to learn how to make deep
connections with youth.

00:56:35.250 --> 00:56:39.170
It's good for their
longevity in the profession.

00:56:39.170 --> 00:56:40.850
The list goes on and on and on.

00:56:40.850 --> 00:56:45.140
Nations, leading researchers
all agreeing about the pathway

00:56:45.140 --> 00:56:47.450
to relationships, particularly
with vulnerable people

00:56:47.450 --> 00:56:50.810
and youth, and why
they matter so much.

00:56:50.810 --> 00:56:52.680
There's no debate in the field.

00:56:52.680 --> 00:56:55.160
The question-- there's no
debate in the research field.

00:56:55.160 --> 00:56:56.900
The question the
practice field has

00:56:56.900 --> 00:57:01.800
to get more complex and more
committed to how, when, where,

00:57:01.800 --> 00:57:04.010
and why.

00:57:04.010 --> 00:57:10.880
Now I'm going to show you a look
in on a teacher's classroom who

00:57:10.880 --> 00:57:14.790
does this as well, if not better
than anybody in the world.

00:57:14.790 --> 00:57:18.560
His name's Mr. Kanamori's
They made a documentary film

00:57:18.560 --> 00:57:20.840
about him when he won the
National Teacher of the Year

00:57:20.840 --> 00:57:23.360
in Japan.

00:57:23.360 --> 00:57:25.380
So this is also a great PD.

00:57:25.380 --> 00:57:28.390
It's called "Children
Full of Life."

00:57:28.390 --> 00:57:30.550
Amazing, because it
follows his classroom

00:57:30.550 --> 00:57:33.310
over the course of the
year, and it disabuses

00:57:33.310 --> 00:57:37.060
people of the belief that
national teachers of the year

00:57:37.060 --> 00:57:39.970
don't have conflict
in their classroom.

00:57:39.970 --> 00:57:43.390
Because he's got hella beef in
his classroom with the kids.

00:57:43.390 --> 00:57:44.140
He gets mad.

00:57:44.140 --> 00:57:46.510
He loses his temper.

00:57:46.510 --> 00:57:47.480
He gets depressed.

00:57:47.480 --> 00:57:48.160
He get sad.

00:57:48.160 --> 00:57:49.960
He feels like he's failing.

00:57:49.960 --> 00:57:52.960
All the range-- the
gamut of emotions.

00:57:52.960 --> 00:57:56.320
And what he says is that I have
the exact same things happening

00:57:56.320 --> 00:57:58.550
in my class as every other
teacher in the country.

00:57:58.550 --> 00:58:01.810
The difference is I
just react differently.

00:58:01.810 --> 00:58:05.410
And I think that there's a sense
that really skilled teachers

00:58:05.410 --> 00:58:08.260
have this special pixie
dust that we blow on kids,

00:58:08.260 --> 00:58:10.305
and it's all good all the time.

00:58:10.305 --> 00:58:12.180
We've got to help all
our teachers understand

00:58:12.180 --> 00:58:14.471
that really good teachers,
the most successful teachers

00:58:14.471 --> 00:58:17.800
have the same beefs in
their classroom as you do.

00:58:17.800 --> 00:58:20.470
They just respond differently.

00:58:20.470 --> 00:58:22.360
Don't try to end the beef.

00:58:22.360 --> 00:58:24.840
Try to learn how to turn
it into teachable moments.

00:58:24.840 --> 00:58:27.670
The meaning is in
the mess, and we keep

00:58:27.670 --> 00:58:30.010
trying to sanitize education.

00:58:30.010 --> 00:58:32.940
It's a human project,
so by definition, it's

00:58:32.940 --> 00:58:34.160
going be messy.

00:58:34.160 --> 00:58:35.937
So can you learn
to love the mess?

00:58:35.937 --> 00:58:37.520
Because that's where
the meaning lies.

00:58:37.520 --> 00:58:39.540
Now you don't want to be
messy all the time, OK?

00:58:39.540 --> 00:58:41.470
Because then it's
just messy, right?

00:58:41.470 --> 00:58:43.680
There's got to be meaning
coming out of the mess.

00:58:43.680 --> 00:58:46.780
So I'm going to introduce
you to Kanamori's class

00:58:46.780 --> 00:58:50.460
as a way to literally
burn in your brain

00:58:50.460 --> 00:58:53.590
an image of what
it looks like when

00:58:53.590 --> 00:58:57.760
a teacher's primary
commitment is relationships.

00:58:57.760 --> 00:58:59.260
And we haven't
tested the sound yet,

00:58:59.260 --> 00:59:02.239
so I'm going to
see how this goes.

00:59:02.239 --> 00:59:03.280
I'm trusting you, Google.

00:59:03.280 --> 00:59:04.089
I'm trusting you.

00:59:04.089 --> 00:59:05.380
It's supposed to be technology.

00:59:05.380 --> 00:59:06.046
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:59:06.046 --> 00:59:09.460
- Late April, Ren [INAUDIBLE]
comes to class for the first

00:59:09.460 --> 00:59:11.740
time in four days.

00:59:11.740 --> 00:59:12.894
His grandmother died.

00:59:24.256 --> 00:59:27.584
In his notebook, Ren
writes about the death,

00:59:27.584 --> 00:59:31.976
the funeral, his loss.

00:59:31.976 --> 00:59:37.344
- [SPEAKING JAPANESE]

00:59:45.750 --> 00:59:47.420
- They were worried.

00:59:47.420 --> 00:59:49.730
They didn't know
why Ren was away.

00:59:49.730 --> 00:59:54.272
Now they're moved at his pain
and saddened by his loss.

00:59:54.272 --> 00:59:59.835
- [SPEAKING JAPANESE]

01:00:22.788 --> 01:00:28.754
- The letter unlocks some
brutal and long-hidden memories.

01:00:28.754 --> 01:00:33.240
- [SPEAKING JAPANESE]

01:00:48.100 --> 01:00:50.560
[CRYING]

01:01:01.880 --> 01:01:05.760
- Mifuyu has been holding down
her memories for more than half

01:01:05.760 --> 01:01:08.206
her life.

01:01:08.206 --> 01:01:13.640
- [SPEAKING JAPANESE]

01:01:36.235 --> 01:01:38.800
- She'd been afraid to
talk about her father.

01:01:38.800 --> 01:01:40.943
She didn't want
to seem different.

01:01:40.943 --> 01:01:42.915
She paid a price.

01:01:42.915 --> 01:01:47.222
- [SPEAKING JAPANESE]

01:02:02.030 --> 01:02:05.570
- Now at last, she
feels safe enough

01:02:05.570 --> 01:02:07.240
to talk about her
missing parent.

01:02:12.685 --> 01:02:18.130
- [SPEAKING JAPANESE]

01:03:00.492 --> 01:03:02.920
- They're trying to understand.

01:03:02.920 --> 01:03:04.820
They all find it painful.

01:03:04.820 --> 01:03:06.962
Some find it unbearable.

01:03:17.610 --> 01:03:21.448
- [SPEAKING JAPANESE]

01:03:21.448 --> 01:03:23.440
[LAUGHTER]

01:03:23.440 --> 01:03:26.050
- Yo Animoto is the
class spark plug.

01:03:26.050 --> 01:03:28.640
High energy, charming.

01:03:28.640 --> 01:03:31.830
Now he's remembering the
death of his grandmother.

01:03:31.830 --> 01:03:36.730
- [SPEAKING JAPANESE]

01:04:24.240 --> 01:04:26.160
[END PLAYBACK]

01:04:28.080 --> 01:04:31.014
JEFF DUNCAN-ANDRADE: That's--
that's master pedagogy.

01:04:33.860 --> 01:04:36.024
But what about time on task?

01:04:36.024 --> 01:04:38.409
[LAUGHTER]

01:04:40.320 --> 01:04:43.590
That's how you get the
highest achievement

01:04:43.590 --> 01:04:46.490
patterns in a nation.

01:04:46.490 --> 01:04:50.660
Relationships, not
drill and kill.

01:04:50.660 --> 01:04:52.730
Because out of
that empathy comes

01:04:52.730 --> 01:04:55.550
the deeper learning,
the connection

01:04:55.550 --> 01:04:57.230
to the concepts and the ideas.

01:04:57.230 --> 01:05:03.050
A reason to read,
a reason to write.

01:05:03.050 --> 01:05:04.750
Not for a test.

01:05:04.750 --> 01:05:10.020
No one in this room
remembers your test scores.

01:05:10.020 --> 01:05:14.100
In the larger scope of your
life, they're irrelevant.

01:05:14.100 --> 01:05:16.380
They matter in terms
of gateway access

01:05:16.380 --> 01:05:18.910
to institutions and power.

01:05:18.910 --> 01:05:21.210
But in terms of building
pluralistic, multiracial

01:05:21.210 --> 01:05:25.510
democracy, they have
almost zero value.

01:05:25.510 --> 01:05:28.330
So what are we trying to build?

01:05:28.330 --> 01:05:30.540
And if it's the
latter, then we've

01:05:30.540 --> 01:05:35.640
got to follow the
research and what we know

01:05:35.640 --> 01:05:38.770
has the biggest impact on
achievement in practice,

01:05:38.770 --> 01:05:39.840
which is relationships.

01:05:43.180 --> 01:05:44.730
Second is relevance.

01:05:44.730 --> 01:05:46.230
We get those kind
of relationships,

01:05:46.230 --> 01:05:47.490
then it's an open question.

01:05:47.490 --> 01:05:51.002
What are we actually
teaching these children?

01:05:51.002 --> 01:05:52.710
Now I'm in a lot of
schools that bring me

01:05:52.710 --> 01:05:55.980
in because they want to do some
iteration of ethnic studies.

01:05:55.980 --> 01:05:58.320
They want to be culturally
and community-responsive,

01:05:58.320 --> 01:05:59.910
culturally relevant.

01:05:59.910 --> 01:06:01.740
I am not a big
fan of checklists,

01:06:01.740 --> 01:06:04.020
but I'm going to give
you one right now.

01:06:04.020 --> 01:06:06.090
If you want to
check whether or not

01:06:06.090 --> 01:06:09.910
your curriculum and
pedagogy in your classrooms

01:06:09.910 --> 01:06:14.070
and in your school is culturally
and community-relevant,

01:06:14.070 --> 01:06:15.890
here's your checklist.

01:06:15.890 --> 01:06:20.550
Does it reflect students'
lives, their communities,

01:06:20.550 --> 01:06:22.770
their families, and their
ethnic, cultural, and

01:06:22.770 --> 01:06:25.160
linguistic histories?

01:06:25.160 --> 01:06:26.552
If it doesn't, the answer's no.

01:06:26.552 --> 01:06:28.510
You're not culturally
and community-responsive.

01:06:28.510 --> 01:06:30.510
If it does, you're
on a good path.

01:06:30.510 --> 01:06:32.990
Well, what that means
is that you're not

01:06:32.990 --> 01:06:34.580
going to have the
same curriculum

01:06:34.580 --> 01:06:40.460
school to school to school,
even in the same city, right?

01:06:40.460 --> 01:06:43.130
That's what it means to be
community and culturally

01:06:43.130 --> 01:06:47.570
responsive, is to first
assess, who are the children

01:06:47.570 --> 01:06:49.700
and families that I serve?

01:06:49.700 --> 01:06:51.380
And what is a
curriculum that connects

01:06:51.380 --> 01:06:55.580
to their lives, their
blocks, their families,

01:06:55.580 --> 01:06:58.100
and their ethnic, cultural,
and linguistic histories?

01:06:58.100 --> 01:07:02.060
That's what it means to
have a relevant education.

01:07:02.060 --> 01:07:06.680
And all of those things can be
scaffolded into Common Core.

01:07:06.680 --> 01:07:09.020
One of the few
upsides of Common Core

01:07:09.020 --> 01:07:12.170
is it actually opens
this window for us

01:07:12.170 --> 01:07:14.480
to be much more dynamic
in the way in which we

01:07:14.480 --> 01:07:17.510
design and deliver curriculum.

01:07:17.510 --> 01:07:20.600
And of course, the
research bears all this out

01:07:20.600 --> 01:07:22.100
across fields.

01:07:22.100 --> 01:07:25.670
There's no debate about whether
or not cultural and community

01:07:25.670 --> 01:07:26.435
relevance matters.

01:07:28.980 --> 01:07:31.360
Here's why.

01:07:31.360 --> 01:07:34.030
First, what we know
is that in classrooms

01:07:34.030 --> 01:07:35.950
where this is
happening, students

01:07:35.950 --> 01:07:39.740
have a stronger sense of self.

01:07:39.740 --> 01:07:43.430
And we know from the research
both from neuroscience

01:07:43.430 --> 01:07:45.350
and from psychology
that there is

01:07:45.350 --> 01:07:47.120
a direct connection
between knowledge

01:07:47.120 --> 01:07:49.490
of self and self-esteem.

01:07:49.490 --> 01:07:53.326
Where did you see self-esteem
in this presentation earlier?

01:07:53.326 --> 01:07:54.220
AUDIENCE: Maslow.

01:07:54.220 --> 01:07:56.310
JEFF DUNCAN-ANDRADE:
Where in Maslow?

01:07:56.310 --> 01:07:57.470
It's not at the top.

01:07:57.470 --> 01:07:58.050
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

01:07:58.050 --> 01:07:59.175
JEFF DUNCAN-ANDRADE: Right.

01:07:59.175 --> 01:08:01.880
It is the window into
self-actualization.

01:08:01.880 --> 01:08:05.670
No human being consistently
self-actualizes

01:08:05.670 --> 01:08:08.490
in an aspect of their life
where they do not have

01:08:08.490 --> 01:08:11.630
self-love, a sense of esteem.

01:08:11.630 --> 01:08:15.140
And we're dealing with kids all
over the country, particularly

01:08:15.140 --> 01:08:17.895
kids of color, that have been
taught to hate themselves.

01:08:17.895 --> 01:08:19.520
Taught to hate the
color of their skin,

01:08:19.520 --> 01:08:22.069
the texture of their hair,
the color of their eyes,

01:08:22.069 --> 01:08:24.859
the language they speak, the
neighborhood they come from,

01:08:24.859 --> 01:08:27.080
their family history.

01:08:27.080 --> 01:08:31.130
That has to be
eradicated in schools.

01:08:31.130 --> 01:08:33.740
How many students
graduate from your schools

01:08:33.740 --> 01:08:36.600
and say, I love myself?

01:08:36.600 --> 01:08:39.871
Because what we know in the
research is that if that's said

01:08:39.871 --> 01:08:42.120
and true, because there's
some kids that say they love

01:08:42.120 --> 01:08:43.920
themselves that really don't.

01:08:43.920 --> 01:08:46.140
But if that's said
and true, that person

01:08:46.140 --> 01:08:49.649
is on a trajectory to success.

01:08:49.649 --> 01:08:50.710
Self-love.

01:08:50.710 --> 01:08:53.310
But I find almost no schools
in the country measured that.

01:08:53.310 --> 01:08:54.779
You know what that means?

01:08:54.779 --> 01:08:56.899
It doesn't matter.

01:08:56.899 --> 01:08:58.819
Because we measure what matters.

01:08:58.819 --> 01:09:02.510
If love matters to you, if
self-esteem matters to you,

01:09:02.510 --> 01:09:05.930
start metricing it in your
classroom and your schools.

01:09:05.930 --> 01:09:09.410
And there are definitely
well-tested measures

01:09:09.410 --> 01:09:10.375
for those things.

01:09:10.375 --> 01:09:12.250
We also know that there's
a direct connection

01:09:12.250 --> 01:09:13.634
between self-esteem and hope.

01:09:17.290 --> 01:09:20.830
Hope has become
particularly centered

01:09:20.830 --> 01:09:26.680
in conversations in the medical
field around vulnerable youth,

01:09:26.680 --> 01:09:30.010
wounded youth, youth exposed
to high levels of trauma

01:09:30.010 --> 01:09:30.910
and toxic stress.

01:09:30.910 --> 01:09:33.040
Because what the
medical field has found

01:09:33.040 --> 01:09:36.250
is that hope is the only
consistent indicator

01:09:36.250 --> 01:09:38.229
that they've been able
to track and measure

01:09:38.229 --> 01:09:41.020
that directly links
to how well students

01:09:41.020 --> 01:09:44.020
navigate through toxic stress.

01:09:44.020 --> 01:09:47.740
The higher their hope levels,
the more resilient they are.

01:09:47.740 --> 01:09:51.310
There is a very clear metric
for hope, what you can measure.

01:09:51.310 --> 01:09:54.370
I use the Children's Hope Scale
in my high school classroom.

01:09:54.370 --> 01:09:57.190
It's the only thing
I baseline is hope,

01:09:57.190 --> 01:09:58.570
because I know the research.

01:09:58.570 --> 01:10:00.610
And I know if I move
the meter on hope,

01:10:00.610 --> 01:10:02.170
the reading, the
writing, the tests

01:10:02.170 --> 01:10:03.530
will take care of themselves.

01:10:03.530 --> 01:10:05.790
And I also know that
if I teach the hell out

01:10:05.790 --> 01:10:07.540
of the reading, the
writing, and the tests

01:10:07.540 --> 01:10:10.760
and I'm not attentive to hope
that it won't move for the kids

01:10:10.760 --> 01:10:12.370
that most need it to move.

01:10:12.370 --> 01:10:16.480
Charles Snyder developed
something called the Children's

01:10:16.480 --> 01:10:20.230
Hope Scale and hope theory.

01:10:20.230 --> 01:10:21.910
It's a very simple
scale that you

01:10:21.910 --> 01:10:24.430
can use to track hope
levels in your classrooms

01:10:24.430 --> 01:10:25.900
and in your schools.

01:10:25.900 --> 01:10:27.820
We know that there's
a direct relationship

01:10:27.820 --> 01:10:31.889
between hope and ability to
interrupt stereotype threat.

01:10:31.889 --> 01:10:34.180
How many of you have heard
of stereotype threat before?

01:10:34.180 --> 01:10:34.820
A few of you?

01:10:34.820 --> 01:10:35.320
OK.

01:10:35.320 --> 01:10:38.470
How many of you test
kids in your schools?

01:10:38.470 --> 01:10:40.377
You guys-- y'all don't test?

01:10:40.377 --> 01:10:41.460
I can just leave now then.

01:10:41.460 --> 01:10:42.940
You good.

01:10:42.940 --> 01:10:44.140
I test kids.

01:10:44.140 --> 01:10:45.190
I'm a teacher.

01:10:45.190 --> 01:10:46.490
I want to know.

01:10:46.490 --> 01:10:48.370
I want to know, do you know?

01:10:48.370 --> 01:10:50.070
I want some recall.

01:10:50.070 --> 01:10:51.340
OK.

01:10:51.340 --> 01:10:52.900
But if you're
going to test kids,

01:10:52.900 --> 01:10:54.250
know the research on testing.

01:10:54.250 --> 01:10:59.110
Claude Steele developed a
concept called stereotype

01:10:59.110 --> 01:11:02.830
threat, because he wanted
to understand-- how many

01:11:02.830 --> 01:11:06.910
of you have students who can do
the work and then they sit exam

01:11:06.910 --> 01:11:08.560
and they choke?

01:11:08.560 --> 01:11:11.290
We now have very clear
neurological science

01:11:11.290 --> 01:11:13.642
on why that happens, OK?

01:11:13.642 --> 01:11:15.100
Here's what happens,
and here's why

01:11:15.100 --> 01:11:20.130
it happens
disproportionately to kids

01:11:20.130 --> 01:11:24.950
of color, poor kids, and girls.

01:11:24.950 --> 01:11:26.510
It's called stereotype threat.

01:11:26.510 --> 01:11:30.230
So what happens when
you sit exam, any exam,

01:11:30.230 --> 01:11:36.290
any test that you believe is a
measure of your innate ability,

01:11:36.290 --> 01:11:39.110
and the stereotype about
your group is that you're not

01:11:39.110 --> 01:11:43.400
innately good at it, you have
a biochemical reaction that

01:11:43.400 --> 01:11:46.940
literally fires inside
your brain and interrupts

01:11:46.940 --> 01:11:49.820
your neural pathways
so that you literally,

01:11:49.820 --> 01:11:53.390
biologically cannot
recall things you know.

01:11:53.390 --> 01:11:55.940
Your neural pathways
get blocked.

01:11:55.940 --> 01:11:58.580
We have crystal clear
research evidence on this.

01:12:01.430 --> 01:12:03.530
So Claude was particularly
interested in why this

01:12:03.530 --> 01:12:05.910
is happening for kids of color.

01:12:05.910 --> 01:12:07.460
So he releases
all this research.

01:12:07.460 --> 01:12:09.990
And probably the
book I'd start with

01:12:09.990 --> 01:12:13.700
is a book called
"Whistling Vivaldi."

01:12:13.700 --> 01:12:16.720
The way in which stereotype
threat affects kids of color

01:12:16.720 --> 01:12:18.380
is very clear to us.

01:12:18.380 --> 01:12:20.240
But the larger research
community is like--

01:12:20.240 --> 01:12:21.190
Claude's at Stanford.

01:12:21.190 --> 01:12:22.510
And they're like, OK, Claude.

01:12:22.510 --> 01:12:24.220
Like, if that's
really true, there

01:12:24.220 --> 01:12:27.110
are stereotypes about
everybody, so stereotype threat

01:12:27.110 --> 01:12:28.550
will affect everybody.

01:12:28.550 --> 01:12:31.340
And Claude goes, yeah, it will.

01:12:31.340 --> 01:12:32.860
But I'm not interested
in everybody.

01:12:32.860 --> 01:12:34.220
I'm focused on kids of color.

01:12:34.220 --> 01:12:36.800
Why do I have to prove it
happens to white people for it

01:12:36.800 --> 01:12:39.650
to matter for people of color?

01:12:39.650 --> 01:12:40.670
You guys go prove that.

01:12:40.670 --> 01:12:42.419
They're like, OK, we will.

01:12:42.419 --> 01:12:44.460
So they said, if it's
true, then it'll definitely

01:12:44.460 --> 01:12:45.450
happen to women.

01:12:45.450 --> 01:12:47.220
Claude said, yep, it will.

01:12:47.220 --> 01:12:50.762
So they conducted a study
with women mathematicians,

01:12:50.762 --> 01:12:52.470
because what's the
stereotype about women

01:12:52.470 --> 01:12:53.550
in math and science?

01:12:53.550 --> 01:12:54.496
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

01:12:54.496 --> 01:12:56.370
JEFF DUNCAN-ANDRADE:
Not innately good at it.

01:12:56.370 --> 01:12:58.890
Not part of your genetic makeup.

01:12:58.890 --> 01:13:01.170
So he took a group--
or this research team

01:13:01.170 --> 01:13:04.410
took a group of women
mathematicians, which

01:13:04.410 --> 01:13:05.956
means they can do what?

01:13:05.956 --> 01:13:06.580
AUDIENCE: Math.

01:13:06.580 --> 01:13:07.663
JEFF DUNCAN-ANDRADE: Math.

01:13:07.663 --> 01:13:08.764
[LAUGHTER]

01:13:09.459 --> 01:13:11.750
And they took them through
this series of problem sets,

01:13:11.750 --> 01:13:16.740
and they did it just fine,
because they're mathematicians.

01:13:16.740 --> 01:13:18.715
And then they sat an exam.

01:13:18.715 --> 01:13:20.715
They put the same problem
sets in front of them,

01:13:20.715 --> 01:13:22.256
and they said, this
test will measure

01:13:22.256 --> 01:13:24.160
your innate
mathematical ability.

01:13:24.160 --> 01:13:25.550
Go.

01:13:25.550 --> 01:13:27.985
And they all underperformed.

01:13:27.985 --> 01:13:29.380
They said, oh my goodness.

01:13:29.380 --> 01:13:31.050
Claude might be right.

01:13:31.050 --> 01:13:32.881
But there's one final test.

01:13:32.881 --> 01:13:35.647
Who's the final test?

01:13:35.647 --> 01:13:36.379
AUDIENCE: Men.

01:13:36.379 --> 01:13:37.670
JEFF DUNCAN-ANDRADE: Which men?

01:13:37.670 --> 01:13:38.503
AUDIENCE: White men.

01:13:38.503 --> 01:13:39.910
JEFF DUNCAN-ANDRADE: White men.

01:13:39.910 --> 01:13:41.650
Because there are stereotypes
about white men too,

01:13:41.650 --> 01:13:42.191
aren't there?

01:13:42.191 --> 01:13:42.900
White men can't--

01:13:42.900 --> 01:13:43.388
AUDIENCE: Jump.

01:13:43.388 --> 01:13:43.876
AUDIENCE: Jump.

01:13:43.876 --> 01:13:44.364
JEFF DUNCAN-ANDRADE: Jump.

01:13:44.364 --> 01:13:44.852
And white--

01:13:44.852 --> 01:13:45.352
[LAUGHTER]

01:13:45.352 --> 01:13:47.600
AUDIENCE: Can't dance.

01:13:47.600 --> 01:13:49.910
JEFF DUNCAN-ANDRADE: And she
added in for extra spite,

01:13:49.910 --> 01:13:50.957
can't dance either.

01:13:50.957 --> 01:13:53.995
[LAUGHTER]

01:13:53.995 --> 01:13:54.870
White men can't jump.

01:13:54.870 --> 01:13:56.540
White men can't dance.

01:13:56.540 --> 01:14:01.650
So UCLA conducts a
study with a group

01:14:01.650 --> 01:14:05.670
of white male undergrads who
were all highly accomplished

01:14:05.670 --> 01:14:07.684
high school athletes.

01:14:07.684 --> 01:14:09.600
Now a lot of people come
to undergrad and say,

01:14:09.600 --> 01:14:11.540
I was an accomplished
high school athlete,

01:14:11.540 --> 01:14:13.410
and it's not even true.

01:14:13.410 --> 01:14:14.400
So they tested it.

01:14:14.400 --> 01:14:17.880
Indeed, these young men were
all very skilled, capable,

01:14:17.880 --> 01:14:19.980
high-end athletes.

01:14:19.980 --> 01:14:22.560
And then they sat an
exam and they said,

01:14:22.560 --> 01:14:25.290
this test will measure your
innate athletic ability.

01:14:25.290 --> 01:14:27.510
And guess what happened?

01:14:27.510 --> 01:14:29.520
They all underperformed.

01:14:29.520 --> 01:14:32.400
And the difference
between white men

01:14:32.400 --> 01:14:35.070
and some women and
kids of color is

01:14:35.070 --> 01:14:37.380
there isn't a stereotype
about white men

01:14:37.380 --> 01:14:39.760
not being good at school.

01:14:39.760 --> 01:14:42.760
So when they sit exam,
the biochemistry registers

01:14:42.760 --> 01:14:44.410
don't shift.

01:14:44.410 --> 01:14:45.730
They know they can do school.

01:14:45.730 --> 01:14:49.080
There's lots of evidence
they can do school.

01:14:49.080 --> 01:14:51.360
But with kids of
color, that question

01:14:51.360 --> 01:14:54.000
is always in the back of your
mind, even if you don't say,

01:14:54.000 --> 01:14:56.440
this test innately
measures your ability.

01:14:56.440 --> 01:14:57.390
You interview kids.

01:14:57.390 --> 01:14:59.850
You find out they think
that the test measures

01:14:59.850 --> 01:15:02.750
their innate ability.

01:15:02.750 --> 01:15:04.430
So Claude is very
clear about what

01:15:04.430 --> 01:15:07.970
you can do with somebody who
needs to test kids to interrupt

01:15:07.970 --> 01:15:09.800
stereotype threat.

01:15:09.800 --> 01:15:11.630
And this is part of
the pattern, but there

01:15:11.630 --> 01:15:15.110
are things you can do tomorrow
when you sit kids exam that you

01:15:15.110 --> 01:15:18.599
can say that will alleviate
some of that neuro blockage

01:15:18.599 --> 01:15:20.390
and will allow them to
perform at the level

01:15:20.390 --> 01:15:22.760
that they're actually at.

01:15:22.760 --> 01:15:24.650
And this creates
what researchers

01:15:24.650 --> 01:15:27.320
call a Pygmalion effect, OK?

01:15:27.320 --> 01:15:30.500
The Pygmalion effect is the
self-fulfilling prophecy.

01:15:30.500 --> 01:15:33.070
I am whatever you say I am.

01:15:33.070 --> 01:15:35.570
Research is crystal clear
that the single biggest

01:15:35.570 --> 01:15:39.770
factor impacting student
achievement in a classroom--

01:15:39.770 --> 01:15:41.780
anybody know what it is?

01:15:41.780 --> 01:15:44.059
Parent income, parent
education, ZIP Code--

01:15:44.059 --> 01:15:45.350
AUDIENCE: Teacher expectations.

01:15:45.350 --> 01:15:47.100
JEFF DUNCAN-ANDRADE:
Teacher expectations.

01:15:47.100 --> 01:15:49.100
Study after study after
study reveals this.

01:15:49.100 --> 01:15:51.530
Teacher expectation is
the number one factor,

01:15:51.530 --> 01:15:53.360
and we have good
research on why,

01:15:53.360 --> 01:15:55.940
because teacher expectation
creates a Pygmalion effect.

01:15:55.940 --> 01:15:57.860
You are always creating
a Pygmalion effect

01:15:57.860 --> 01:15:58.790
in your classroom.

01:15:58.790 --> 01:16:01.160
That's a fact, always.

01:16:01.160 --> 01:16:03.920
There is always a
Pygmalion effect going on.

01:16:03.920 --> 01:16:07.870
The question is whether it's a
positive or a negative one, OK?

01:16:07.870 --> 01:16:10.720
The negative Pygmalion effect
is you think I'm not smart,

01:16:10.720 --> 01:16:11.840
I must not be smart.

01:16:11.840 --> 01:16:15.360
The positive Pygmalion effect
is you think I'm smart,

01:16:15.360 --> 01:16:18.260
I must be smart.

01:16:18.260 --> 01:16:21.466
And this is what Carol Dweck's
work has lifted up for us.

01:16:21.466 --> 01:16:23.090
Now I'm in schools
all over the country

01:16:23.090 --> 01:16:24.689
that are misusing
Carol Dweck's work.

01:16:24.689 --> 01:16:27.230
Carol Dweck-- how many of you
are familiar with Carol Dweck's

01:16:27.230 --> 01:16:27.750
work?

01:16:27.750 --> 01:16:28.250
Oh, yeah.

01:16:28.250 --> 01:16:29.310
That's what I thought.

01:16:29.310 --> 01:16:30.543
It's all the rage.

01:16:30.543 --> 01:16:32.022
[LAUGHTER]

01:16:33.010 --> 01:16:37.660
Have you been-- checked out
Carol's latest lectures?

01:16:37.660 --> 01:16:43.430
She's gone back on the lecture
circuit to rage on schools

01:16:43.430 --> 01:16:45.906
for misusing her research.

01:16:45.906 --> 01:16:47.780
Because I'm in schools
all the time that say,

01:16:47.780 --> 01:16:49.490
yeah, we're working
on growth mindset.

01:16:49.490 --> 01:16:50.810
I'm like, yeah, oh, who are
you working on that with?

01:16:50.810 --> 01:16:51.380
And they're like, the kids.

01:16:51.380 --> 01:16:52.963
We're developing
kids' growth mindset.

01:16:56.340 --> 01:16:58.242
Carol's like, oh, shit.

01:16:58.242 --> 01:16:59.210
[LAUGHTER]

01:16:59.210 --> 01:17:02.010
OK, let me just lay it
out for you plain, right?

01:17:02.010 --> 01:17:03.300
Who needs a growth mindset?

01:17:03.300 --> 01:17:04.374
AUDIENCE: Teachers.

01:17:04.374 --> 01:17:05.790
JEFF DUNCAN-ANDRADE:
The grownups.

01:17:05.790 --> 01:17:07.560
OK, the grownups.

01:17:07.560 --> 01:17:09.870
What Carol Dweck says very
clearly in her research

01:17:09.870 --> 01:17:12.420
is that the mindset
of the children

01:17:12.420 --> 01:17:15.510
reflects the mindset
of the adults.

01:17:15.510 --> 01:17:17.760
So if you want to change
the mindset of the children,

01:17:17.760 --> 01:17:19.718
you've got to change the
mindset of the adults.

01:17:19.718 --> 01:17:21.730
The growth mindset work
is for the grownups.

01:17:21.730 --> 01:17:23.520
And when grownups
have a growth mindset,

01:17:23.520 --> 01:17:25.065
kids come along just fine.

01:17:25.065 --> 01:17:26.940
So if you're finding
children in your schools

01:17:26.940 --> 01:17:29.820
don't have growth mindset,
then work on the adults that

01:17:29.820 --> 01:17:32.670
are around them.

01:17:32.670 --> 01:17:34.740
We're short on
time, so I'm going

01:17:34.740 --> 01:17:37.540
to blow into the third one.

01:17:37.540 --> 01:17:40.121
You're not going to get
to see the [INAUDIBLE]..

01:17:40.121 --> 01:17:40.620
Sorry.

01:17:40.620 --> 01:17:43.434
Hey, you know-- now she's
giving me the two-minute mark.

01:17:43.434 --> 01:17:44.850
Or are you throwing
up peace sign?

01:17:44.850 --> 01:17:46.705
[LAUGHTER]

01:17:47.205 --> 01:17:51.450
We're going to end
with responsibility.

01:17:51.450 --> 01:17:54.930
Because at the end of the
day, that's the driver.

01:17:54.930 --> 01:17:58.534
Can we hold our responsibility?

01:17:58.534 --> 01:18:00.700
Bruce Perry's considered
the nation's leading expert

01:18:00.700 --> 01:18:03.270
on child trauma.

01:18:03.270 --> 01:18:05.390
So if you are working
with kids that

01:18:05.390 --> 01:18:08.940
are experiencing mild to severe
exposure to toxic stress,

01:18:08.940 --> 01:18:12.410
they are going to have
trauma registers, OK?

01:18:12.410 --> 01:18:15.020
Bruce's book, "The Boy
Who Was Raised as a Dog"

01:18:15.020 --> 01:18:17.450
is my primer when I'm
working with schools that

01:18:17.450 --> 01:18:18.770
have high levels of trauma.

01:18:18.770 --> 01:18:20.510
It is awesome.

01:18:20.510 --> 01:18:22.940
His work is awesome,
and this book

01:18:22.940 --> 01:18:25.496
is a great PD item for teachers.

01:18:25.496 --> 01:18:26.870
You can do one
chapter at a time,

01:18:26.870 --> 01:18:29.720
because every chapter's
an independent case study.

01:18:29.720 --> 01:18:33.080
And it will literally
change the way

01:18:33.080 --> 01:18:37.220
that you interact with kids that
quote, unquote, "misbehave,"

01:18:37.220 --> 01:18:39.179
because you'll read their
behavior differently.

01:18:39.179 --> 01:18:40.803
And when you read
behavior differently,

01:18:40.803 --> 01:18:41.810
you respond differently.

01:18:41.810 --> 01:18:45.770
If you see it as misbehavior,
then you'll punish it.

01:18:45.770 --> 01:18:48.080
If you see it as the
result of trauma,

01:18:48.080 --> 01:18:50.280
then you'll try to heal it.

01:18:50.280 --> 01:18:53.887
There's all kinds of
neurology behind that.

01:18:53.887 --> 01:18:55.470
Some other light
reading, just in case

01:18:55.470 --> 01:18:57.630
you get bored over the summer.

01:18:57.630 --> 01:18:58.890
Robert Putnam.

01:18:58.890 --> 01:19:01.320
Oxford recalls Robert Putnam
the world's most influential

01:19:01.320 --> 01:19:02.890
scholar.

01:19:02.890 --> 01:19:05.370
OK, it's not actually "Bowling
Alone" that I recommend.

01:19:05.370 --> 01:19:07.050
I put "Bowling Alone" up there
because that's the one that

01:19:07.050 --> 01:19:07.841
put him on the map.

01:19:07.841 --> 01:19:10.890
He just released another
book called "Our Kids," which

01:19:10.890 --> 01:19:15.210
is one of the best
political economist analyses

01:19:15.210 --> 01:19:17.910
of the role of public
schools in creating

01:19:17.910 --> 01:19:21.150
a social apartheid or a
pluralistic, multiracial

01:19:21.150 --> 01:19:22.050
democracy.

01:19:22.050 --> 01:19:24.120
Putnam is at Harvard's
Kennedy School.

01:19:24.120 --> 01:19:29.880
He concludes that we are rapidly
approaching social apartheid,

01:19:29.880 --> 01:19:32.530
if not already achieved it.

01:19:32.530 --> 01:19:37.590
"Unnatural Causes" is an
amazing film series from PBS.

01:19:37.590 --> 01:19:40.450
I think they now
have eight films out.

01:19:40.450 --> 01:19:44.010
It has a great website with
tons of resources for teachers.

01:19:44.010 --> 01:19:46.820
It's the largest study ever
connected cross-discipline--

01:19:46.820 --> 01:19:49.590
or ever conducted
cross-disciplinary

01:19:49.590 --> 01:19:51.720
on the impact of inequality.

01:19:51.720 --> 01:19:53.940
It's a global
study of inequality

01:19:53.940 --> 01:19:56.130
and its relationship
to health outcomes.

01:19:56.130 --> 01:20:00.390
And conclusive field to
field is that the biggest

01:20:00.390 --> 01:20:03.760
threat to health on the
planet is inequality.

01:20:03.760 --> 01:20:06.900
So if you want a healthy
classroom or a healthy school,

01:20:06.900 --> 01:20:10.090
you have to eradicate
all forms of inequality.

01:20:10.090 --> 01:20:12.420
No oppression Olympics.

01:20:12.420 --> 01:20:13.969
You've got to pay
attention to race.

01:20:13.969 --> 01:20:15.510
You've got to pay
attention to class.

01:20:15.510 --> 01:20:16.970
You've got to pay
attention to gender.

01:20:16.970 --> 01:20:18.928
You've got to pay attention
to sexual identity.

01:20:18.928 --> 01:20:21.510
You've got to pay attention
to xenophobia, language.

01:20:21.510 --> 01:20:25.920
All forms of inequality,
odious, intolerable.

01:20:25.920 --> 01:20:28.080
And when that is what
we see in schools,

01:20:28.080 --> 01:20:30.710
that's what we'll
see in our society.

01:20:30.710 --> 01:20:33.390
Because if for 13 years
you go to an institution

01:20:33.390 --> 01:20:36.210
where inequality
is unacceptable,

01:20:36.210 --> 01:20:37.680
you become an
adult that believes

01:20:37.680 --> 01:20:39.840
inequality is unacceptable.

01:20:39.840 --> 01:20:42.960
But the truth is schools
are a social mirror,

01:20:42.960 --> 01:20:44.730
and the same
radicalized inequality

01:20:44.730 --> 01:20:49.420
that we see in the society
gets normed in schools.

01:20:49.420 --> 01:20:52.510
And then last, Michelle
Alexander's "The New Jim Crow"

01:20:52.510 --> 01:20:54.520
for my money is
the best analysis

01:20:54.520 --> 01:20:58.280
of the relationship between
schools and the prison system.

01:20:58.280 --> 01:20:59.770
I want every
educator that I work

01:20:59.770 --> 01:21:03.190
with to understand that
writing a referral on a child

01:21:03.190 --> 01:21:05.590
is not a benign act.

01:21:05.590 --> 01:21:10.380
You put pen to paper, and
we have very clear evidence

01:21:10.380 --> 01:21:13.770
that there is a connection
between referral and pathway

01:21:13.770 --> 01:21:15.120
to juvie.

01:21:15.120 --> 01:21:17.070
And we have very clear
research evidence

01:21:17.070 --> 01:21:20.100
that there is a clear connection
between the pathway to juvie

01:21:20.100 --> 01:21:22.260
and the pathway to the pen.

01:21:22.260 --> 01:21:25.620
Schools have to change the
way we discipline kids,

01:21:25.620 --> 01:21:27.050
because we don't.

01:21:27.050 --> 01:21:28.590
We punish them.

01:21:28.590 --> 01:21:31.350
And discipline and punishment
are not the same thing.

01:21:31.350 --> 01:21:34.260
Read Michel Foucault. We
have conflated those things

01:21:34.260 --> 01:21:35.670
in schools.

01:21:35.670 --> 01:21:37.260
And I guarantee
you, if you start

01:21:37.260 --> 01:21:41.790
calling suspension,
expulsion, and office

01:21:41.790 --> 01:21:45.857
referrals punishment,
they'll go down.

01:21:45.857 --> 01:21:47.690
They'll go down, because
then you're saying,

01:21:47.690 --> 01:21:49.890
so you want to punish this kid.

01:21:49.890 --> 01:21:51.117
And people-- oh, no, no, no.

01:21:51.117 --> 01:21:52.200
I want to discipline them.

01:21:52.200 --> 01:21:52.699
OK.

01:21:52.699 --> 01:21:57.150
Well, discipline comes from
the Latin discipulus, which

01:21:57.150 --> 01:21:58.930
means rigorous repetition--

01:21:58.930 --> 01:22:01.350
or rigorous training
through repetition.

01:22:01.350 --> 01:22:05.560
Can you give a child rigorous
training through repetition

01:22:05.560 --> 01:22:07.960
if they're suspended?

01:22:07.960 --> 01:22:08.460
Yeah.

01:22:08.460 --> 01:22:11.250
You can give them rigorous
repetition in suspension,

01:22:11.250 --> 01:22:13.360
and that's what
happens, isn't it?

01:22:13.360 --> 01:22:16.050
There is no evidence
in the research field

01:22:16.050 --> 01:22:18.330
that punishment
changes behavior.

01:22:18.330 --> 01:22:20.730
There is very clear evidence
in the research field

01:22:20.730 --> 01:22:22.380
that discipline
changes behavior.

01:22:22.380 --> 01:22:25.110
Discipline is a
process of inclusion.

01:22:25.110 --> 01:22:27.900
Punishment is a
process of exclusion.

01:22:27.900 --> 01:22:29.924
Do you discipline kids
or do you punish them?

01:22:29.924 --> 01:22:31.590
Make sure you understand
the difference.

01:22:31.590 --> 01:22:36.480
