Like, I could
apply it right now.

01:32:57.410 --> 01:32:58.200
Like, oh.

01:32:58.200 --> 01:33:00.530
It changed the way
I saw certain kids.

01:33:00.530 --> 01:33:03.815
So it really depends on
the problem of practice

01:33:03.815 --> 01:33:06.860
that the educator
is trying to unlock.

01:33:06.860 --> 01:33:10.190
But typically, that's
with, like, I'm

01:33:10.190 --> 01:33:12.230
trying to figure out how
to connect to this kid

01:33:12.230 --> 01:33:14.660
that I can't figure out
how to connect to, right?

01:33:14.660 --> 01:33:16.349
That's typically the
biggest challenge

01:33:16.349 --> 01:33:17.390
that I see with teachers.

01:33:17.390 --> 01:33:21.230
This kid is disruptive, won't
do the work, they're defiant,

01:33:21.230 --> 01:33:24.050
whatever the story is.

01:33:24.050 --> 01:33:28.010
And so depending on the
context in which you teach,

01:33:28.010 --> 01:33:31.720
I would start teachers off
either with Perry's book,

01:33:31.720 --> 01:33:35.180
OK, Bruce Perry's book, "The
Boy That Was Raised as a Dog,"

01:33:35.180 --> 01:33:37.700
because inevitably what's
happening with that quote,

01:33:37.700 --> 01:33:41.630
unquote, "defiant" kid is that
they're carrying a trauma load,

01:33:41.630 --> 01:33:42.690
right?

01:33:42.690 --> 01:33:45.110
Their neurology and
their biochemistry's

01:33:45.110 --> 01:33:49.850
all off whack because they're
not feeling safe, right?

01:33:49.850 --> 01:33:53.210
And so to the degree that a
teacher can understand that--

01:33:53.210 --> 01:33:55.070
and Perry helps you
understand, like,

01:33:55.070 --> 01:33:57.009
what's going on inside the kid.

01:33:57.009 --> 01:33:59.300
And when you understand what's
going on inside the kid,

01:33:59.300 --> 01:34:02.510
then you read the outer
portrayal of those things

01:34:02.510 --> 01:34:04.490
differently.

01:34:04.490 --> 01:34:08.420
So the other thing that
really impacted my classroom

01:34:08.420 --> 01:34:12.782
practice a lot was "Unnatural
Causes," that film series.

01:34:12.782 --> 01:34:14.240
Because there's
also a website that

01:34:14.240 --> 01:34:18.320
hosts it that has lots and lots
of very practical curriculum

01:34:18.320 --> 01:34:21.650
resources, trainings, all
these things that teachers

01:34:21.650 --> 01:34:23.030
can access.

01:34:23.030 --> 01:34:26.000
But at the end of the day, I
think typically the advice that

01:34:26.000 --> 01:34:29.360
I give to teachers that are
struggling with a particular

01:34:29.360 --> 01:34:34.400
student is don't try to fix
that problem in the classroom,

01:34:34.400 --> 01:34:37.380
because you almost
certainly can't.

01:34:37.380 --> 01:34:42.020
So can you create the conditions
to build a relationship

01:34:42.020 --> 01:34:45.380
with that child outside
of the classroom?

01:34:45.380 --> 01:34:48.920
And the truth is that
every single teacher

01:34:48.920 --> 01:34:54.070
I've ever worked with already
has the skill set they need.

01:34:54.070 --> 01:34:55.470
They're not lacking, OK?

01:34:55.470 --> 01:34:57.090
Because every teacher
that you might

01:34:57.090 --> 01:35:00.120
be working with that's
struggling with something,

01:35:00.120 --> 01:35:04.430
they have a good relationship
with somebody in their life.

01:35:04.430 --> 01:35:07.470
So what is that evidence of?

01:35:07.470 --> 01:35:08.470
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

01:35:08.470 --> 01:35:09.070
JEFF DUNCAN-ANDRADE:
That they know

01:35:09.070 --> 01:35:11.260
how to build a good
relationship, right?

01:35:11.260 --> 01:35:14.710
And so what's happening
is that they're

01:35:14.710 --> 01:35:19.030
mismatching who they are in
that positive relationship

01:35:19.030 --> 01:35:23.670
and who they are with that kid
that they're in conflict with.

01:35:23.670 --> 01:35:26.050
And because they have
power in the relationship,

01:35:26.050 --> 01:35:28.840
they're wanting the kid
to change first, right?

01:35:28.840 --> 01:35:31.660
When this kid shows
up properly, right?

01:35:31.660 --> 01:35:35.320
When they show up with respect,
then I'll be their teacher.

01:35:35.320 --> 01:35:39.040
That's actually a violation
of our moral responsibility

01:35:39.040 --> 01:35:40.030
as a teacher.

01:35:40.030 --> 01:35:41.590
In New Zealand,
they actually have

01:35:41.590 --> 01:35:45.256
to sign-- teachers have to
sign the Hippocratic oath.

01:35:45.256 --> 01:35:46.630
Y'all know what
the Hippocratic--

01:35:46.630 --> 01:35:48.546
anybody not know what
the Hippocratic oath is?

01:35:48.546 --> 01:35:50.020
That's the oath
that doctors take.

01:35:50.020 --> 01:35:52.020
And what's the
main line in there?

01:35:52.020 --> 01:35:53.320
AUDIENCE: Do no harm.

01:35:53.320 --> 01:35:56.740
JEFF DUNCAN-ANDRADE: First
rule, do no harm, right?

01:35:56.740 --> 01:36:00.070
And so I start there
with teachers, right?

01:36:00.070 --> 01:36:04.681
What is-- have them analyze
the best relationship

01:36:04.681 --> 01:36:05.680
they have in their life.

01:36:05.680 --> 01:36:07.000
What are the components of it?

01:36:07.000 --> 01:36:08.110
How do they act?

01:36:08.110 --> 01:36:12.400
And specifically, how do
you act under conflict?

01:36:12.400 --> 01:36:17.440
Because we romanticize our
relationships in this country.

01:36:17.440 --> 01:36:20.860
We act as if conflict
is a bad thing.

01:36:20.860 --> 01:36:23.510
And the truth is that the
tightest relationship you have,

01:36:23.510 --> 01:36:25.960
whether it's with your
homies or with your partner

01:36:25.960 --> 01:36:30.730
or with your children,
there's always conflict.

01:36:33.410 --> 01:36:37.430
And we have this story that
we tell ourselves that love

01:36:37.430 --> 01:36:40.640
is the absence of conflict.

01:36:40.640 --> 01:36:43.940
Because love in this society
is super pollyannish.

01:36:43.940 --> 01:36:45.735
It's all based on
"The Notebook."

01:36:45.735 --> 01:36:47.890
[LAUGHTER]

01:36:48.660 --> 01:36:50.870
Everything's going to
be OK in the end, right?

01:36:50.870 --> 01:36:53.260
No, it's not.

01:36:53.260 --> 01:36:56.290
Love is not the absence
of conflict, OK?

01:36:56.290 --> 01:36:57.820
Give this nugget
to your teachers.

01:36:57.820 --> 01:36:59.740
Love is not the
absence of conflict.

01:36:59.740 --> 01:37:02.620
Love is the presence of conflict
with the courage, character,

01:37:02.620 --> 01:37:05.500
and commitment to
find your way through.

01:37:05.500 --> 01:37:09.040
And that is the
main divide I find

01:37:09.040 --> 01:37:11.290
between the most successful
teachers and the least

01:37:11.290 --> 01:37:15.970
successful teachers, is the
least successful teachers abhor

01:37:15.970 --> 01:37:17.320
conflict.

01:37:17.320 --> 01:37:19.750
They resent it.

01:37:19.750 --> 01:37:23.430
They want it to go away.

01:37:23.430 --> 01:37:24.870
They want no mess.

01:37:24.870 --> 01:37:28.492
And what I tell those teachers
is, get an office job.

01:37:28.492 --> 01:37:33.300
If you want predictability,
get the hell out of teaching.

01:37:33.300 --> 01:37:37.380
I've been teaching 25
years, and the minute

01:37:37.380 --> 01:37:41.910
I think I got it licked, I get
one in the back of the head.

01:37:41.910 --> 01:37:43.050
Like, no way!

01:37:43.050 --> 01:37:45.000
How'd you get me?

01:37:45.000 --> 01:37:50.250
That girl that you heard,
when she started my class,

01:37:50.250 --> 01:37:51.680
I was starting my 18th year.

01:37:51.680 --> 01:37:55.040
I had all these awards.

01:37:55.040 --> 01:37:58.940
And she's my neighbor.

01:37:58.940 --> 01:38:02.270
And one of my points of
pride in my 18 years--

01:38:02.270 --> 01:38:03.671
pride cometh before the--

01:38:03.671 --> 01:38:04.296
AUDIENCE: Fall.

01:38:04.296 --> 01:38:05.005
JEFF DUNCAN-ANDRADE: Mm-hmm.

01:38:05.005 --> 01:38:05.960
So here it comes.

01:38:05.960 --> 01:38:09.590
One of my points of pride was
that in 18 years in deep East

01:38:09.590 --> 01:38:15.248
Oakland, I'd never had a
fight in my class, ever.

01:38:15.248 --> 01:38:21.010
And the first day, that girl
hops off a fight in my class.

01:38:21.010 --> 01:38:22.660
My damn neighbor--

01:38:22.660 --> 01:38:23.830
[LAUGHTER]

01:38:23.830 --> 01:38:27.460
--breaks my streak of 18 years.

01:38:27.460 --> 01:38:31.580
And a lot of teachers would
have resented her for that,

01:38:31.580 --> 01:38:35.920
and I loved her for it,
because she forced me to grow.

01:38:35.920 --> 01:38:37.480
And all those awards--

01:38:37.480 --> 01:38:41.110
when I get awards,
I put them in boxes,

01:38:41.110 --> 01:38:42.550
because that's who I was.

01:38:42.550 --> 01:38:45.024
It's not who I'm becoming.

01:38:45.024 --> 01:38:46.190
And she reminded me of that.

01:38:46.190 --> 01:38:48.065
You've got to become
somebody else right now,

01:38:48.065 --> 01:38:50.320
because I'm in your class.

01:38:50.320 --> 01:38:51.800
Right?

01:38:51.800 --> 01:38:54.200
And a lot of teachers,
they'd have all awards,

01:38:54.200 --> 01:38:56.600
do you know who I am?

01:38:56.600 --> 01:39:01.480
That same class two years
later, Harvard brought me up,

01:39:01.480 --> 01:39:04.670
and me and Arne Duncan
were the keynote speakers.

01:39:04.670 --> 01:39:06.170
Arne Duncan went
first, and then I

01:39:06.170 --> 01:39:08.461
went on and explained why
everything he said was wrong.

01:39:08.461 --> 01:39:10.610
[LAUGHTER]

01:39:11.210 --> 01:39:14.450
And so I fly back from Boston.

01:39:14.450 --> 01:39:18.170
I get in, like, 2:00
in the morning to SFO.

01:39:18.170 --> 01:39:21.320
Go back to my house,
and first period I'm

01:39:21.320 --> 01:39:25.190
in my class teaching
11th grade English.

01:39:25.190 --> 01:39:30.080
And this boy in my class,
like, just gives me the--

01:39:30.080 --> 01:39:31.580
like, to the point
where I literally

01:39:31.580 --> 01:39:33.450
started having homicidal
thoughts about him.

01:39:33.450 --> 01:39:34.283
Like, in the moment.

01:39:34.283 --> 01:39:36.340
Like, dude, I'm
going to kill you.

01:39:36.340 --> 01:39:38.600
And my first reaction to
him when he was doing this

01:39:38.600 --> 01:39:40.059
was, I almost--

01:39:40.059 --> 01:39:40.850
I almost said this.

01:39:40.850 --> 01:39:42.770
I almost said, do
you know who I am?

01:39:42.770 --> 01:39:43.994
[LAUGHTER]

01:39:43.994 --> 01:39:46.970
Like, I was just with
Arne Duncan, you asshole.

01:39:46.970 --> 01:39:51.200
[LAUGHTER]

01:39:51.200 --> 01:39:54.680
And then I remember,
he doesn't give a shit

01:39:54.680 --> 01:39:57.020
about Harvard or Arne Duncan.

01:39:57.020 --> 01:39:59.990
He's showing up with
all his woundedness.

01:39:59.990 --> 01:40:03.660
Can you hold me like this?

01:40:03.660 --> 01:40:06.760
Because you say
you care about me.

01:40:06.760 --> 01:40:08.660
And what I try to get
teachers to understand

01:40:08.660 --> 01:40:13.160
is the most wounded children
speak the most truth,

01:40:13.160 --> 01:40:16.100
and we resent them for it.

01:40:16.100 --> 01:40:18.020
Because the most
wounded children

01:40:18.020 --> 01:40:20.460
don't even try to
cover it up anymore.

01:40:20.460 --> 01:40:24.960
They reveal to us the darkest
corners of our society.

01:40:24.960 --> 01:40:28.640
That's what that girl told
you, that she showed me

01:40:28.640 --> 01:40:29.850
on the first day.

01:40:29.850 --> 01:40:31.490
I'm wounded.

01:40:31.490 --> 01:40:34.520
And I know who you think you
are, 18-year vet with all

01:40:34.520 --> 01:40:35.054
your awards.

01:40:35.054 --> 01:40:37.220
Your reputation ripples
throughout the neighborhood.

01:40:37.220 --> 01:40:39.200
And for that reason,
I'm coming in here.

01:40:39.200 --> 01:40:41.420
I'm going to fuck up your
class on the first day.

01:40:41.420 --> 01:40:43.340
[LAUGHTER]

01:40:43.340 --> 01:40:46.430
Because everybody
says, you're Jeff.

01:40:46.430 --> 01:40:48.890
Everybody says, you
love all your students.

01:40:48.890 --> 01:40:51.080
Everybody says,
you'll go to juvie.

01:40:51.080 --> 01:40:52.100
You'll go to jail.

01:40:52.100 --> 01:40:53.330
You'll go to the streets.

01:40:53.330 --> 01:40:56.449
Everybody says, but you
won't do that for me.

01:40:56.449 --> 01:40:57.490
You won't do that for me.

01:40:57.490 --> 01:41:00.031
I know you won't, and I'm going
to prove it on the first day.

01:41:00.031 --> 01:41:05.120
I'm just going to fire on this
girl right here just to see.

01:41:05.120 --> 01:41:10.705
And once we got the fight
stopped, and she's waiting--

01:41:10.705 --> 01:41:11.831
and what's she waiting for?

01:41:11.831 --> 01:41:12.705
AUDIENCE: Punishment.

01:41:12.705 --> 01:41:13.600
AUDIENCE: Reaction.

01:41:13.600 --> 01:41:15.891
JEFF DUNCAN-ANDRADE: She's
waiting to go to the office.

01:41:15.891 --> 01:41:17.740
She's waiting for the referral.

01:41:17.740 --> 01:41:21.240
And I said, sit your ass down.

01:41:21.240 --> 01:41:23.050
Fuck up my 18 years.

01:41:23.050 --> 01:41:25.375
[LAUGHTER]

01:41:25.375 --> 01:41:26.630
Sit your ass down.

01:41:29.150 --> 01:41:31.025
And you know what
her reaction was?

01:41:31.025 --> 01:41:32.750
She literally says, no.

01:41:32.750 --> 01:41:35.480
You have to send
me to the office.

01:41:35.480 --> 01:41:38.930
And I said, I don't send
people to the office.

01:41:38.930 --> 01:41:41.455
Because when I was your age,
I got sent to the office.

01:41:44.240 --> 01:41:49.610
You're here because I love
you, and you did some shit

01:41:49.610 --> 01:41:50.930
that makes me want to kill you.

01:41:50.930 --> 01:41:52.980
[LAUGHTER]

01:41:52.980 --> 01:41:56.880
And so we're going to have
to go from kill to love.

01:41:56.880 --> 01:42:00.560
And in order for that to
happen, we're going to talk.

01:42:00.560 --> 01:42:02.820
No, you've got to
send me to the office.

01:42:02.820 --> 01:42:05.600
No, I don't.

01:42:05.600 --> 01:42:08.420
That's how our
relationship started.

01:42:08.420 --> 01:42:11.210
And a year later, she's
telling that story.

01:42:14.680 --> 01:42:18.070
Now I know how practical that
is, because this work ain't

01:42:18.070 --> 01:42:19.360
always practical, right?

01:42:19.360 --> 01:42:20.085
It's not clean.

01:42:20.085 --> 01:42:20.960
It's not [INAUDIBLE].

01:42:20.960 --> 01:42:24.220
Can you coach
people into the mess

01:42:24.220 --> 01:42:26.680
and then create the conditions
whereby they can narrate,

01:42:26.680 --> 01:42:29.020
how do I get out of this mess?

01:42:29.020 --> 01:42:30.530
Perry can give you
some good stuff.

01:42:30.530 --> 01:42:32.530
"Unnatural Causes" can
give you some good stuff.

01:42:32.530 --> 01:42:34.238
But at the end of the
day, what I find is

01:42:34.238 --> 01:42:36.880
most teachers already know
what they're supposed to do.

01:42:36.880 --> 01:42:40.250
They're just loath to
do it, because they

01:42:40.250 --> 01:42:43.460
haven't figured out how to
find themselves in that child.

01:42:43.460 --> 01:42:45.230
So the practical
piece I will give you

01:42:45.230 --> 01:42:47.430
is actually from my ancestors.

01:42:47.430 --> 01:42:49.820
So I come from the
[INAUDIBLE],, which

01:42:49.820 --> 01:42:53.300
connects me to the Mayan
and the [INAUDIBLE] people.

01:42:53.300 --> 01:42:58.250
And the Mayans had a story, a
principle called In Lak'ech.

01:42:58.250 --> 01:43:02.570
And In Lak'ech became an
increasingly popularized

01:43:02.570 --> 01:43:05.690
concept and term in education
because of the work of the Raza

01:43:05.690 --> 01:43:08.930
Studies program in Tucson
Unified who taught me a lot

01:43:08.930 --> 01:43:12.500
about my history and my
culture and In Lak'ech.

01:43:12.500 --> 01:43:17.120
And In Lak'ech the story
of the smoking mirror.

01:43:17.120 --> 01:43:20.330
We would teach all our
children this idea.

01:43:20.330 --> 01:43:22.990
And the idea is
that every living

01:43:22.990 --> 01:43:26.830
being that you come across
is a smoking mirror.

01:43:26.830 --> 01:43:28.334
That is not the question.

01:43:28.334 --> 01:43:29.750
The question is
whether or not you

01:43:29.750 --> 01:43:31.791
can muster the courage,
character, and commitment

01:43:31.791 --> 01:43:33.140
to clear the smoke away.

01:43:33.140 --> 01:43:35.990
Because if you do,
what will you see?

01:43:35.990 --> 01:43:37.490
You'll see yourself.

01:43:37.490 --> 01:43:40.070
That's the barrier
for most teachers.

01:43:40.070 --> 01:43:42.110
Lisa Delpit called it
in one of her books,

01:43:42.110 --> 01:43:43.992
"Other People's Children."

01:43:43.992 --> 01:43:45.950
And as long as they're
other people's children,

01:43:45.950 --> 01:43:47.039
they go to the office.

01:43:47.039 --> 01:43:48.830
As long as they're
other people's children,

01:43:48.830 --> 01:43:49.538
they go to juvie.

01:43:49.538 --> 01:43:50.480
They need tough love.

01:43:50.480 --> 01:43:52.180
They need discipline.

01:43:52.180 --> 01:43:53.900
They need punishment.

01:43:53.900 --> 01:43:56.930
But if it's your son,
if it's your daughter,

01:43:56.930 --> 01:43:57.980
the smoke is cleared.

01:43:57.980 --> 01:43:58.520
You know.

01:43:58.520 --> 01:44:02.300
You'll try every angle, every--
you ain't going to the office.

01:44:02.300 --> 01:44:06.060
There is no way in hell I'm
sending Amaru or Taiyari

01:44:06.060 --> 01:44:08.354
to the damn principal.

01:44:08.354 --> 01:44:09.020
They're my sons.

01:44:11.750 --> 01:44:14.240
I feel that way about
every kid I teach.

01:44:14.240 --> 01:44:15.740
You are my son.

01:44:15.740 --> 01:44:17.900
You are my daughter.

01:44:17.900 --> 01:44:20.450
I am not sending
you to somebody else

01:44:20.450 --> 01:44:23.270
to fix you, because
you're not broken.

01:44:23.270 --> 01:44:25.220
I have to figure out
what's in your way.

01:44:25.220 --> 01:44:28.620
That is the principle teaching
of all of our ancestors,

01:44:28.620 --> 01:44:30.620
and we've lost our way
around that because we've

01:44:30.620 --> 01:44:34.380
been become technocratic
and mechanical in teaching.

01:44:34.380 --> 01:44:36.980
Teaching is about
relationships, and relationships

01:44:36.980 --> 01:44:40.059
is about work and pain.

01:44:40.059 --> 01:44:41.600
And the deepest
relationships we have

01:44:41.600 --> 01:44:44.270
are with people that we
went through that pain.

01:44:44.270 --> 01:44:45.760
We cleared the smoke away.

01:44:45.760 --> 01:44:48.500
And the honest truth
is that the kids that

01:44:48.500 --> 01:44:51.170
are going to be the
toughest to reach

01:44:51.170 --> 01:44:54.850
are the ones with
the most smoke.

01:44:54.850 --> 01:44:57.220
And that makes sense,
because they're on fire.

01:44:57.220 --> 01:44:58.960
Their lives are on fire.

01:44:58.960 --> 01:45:01.240
So it's going to be way
more smoke to clear.

01:45:01.240 --> 01:45:05.285
Harder work to find
yourself in that child.

01:45:05.285 --> 01:45:06.910
But if you've taught
as long as I have,

01:45:06.910 --> 01:45:11.470
you know that those are
the kids that come back.

01:45:11.470 --> 01:45:13.510
They're worth it.

01:45:13.510 --> 01:45:17.260
But that's what we've got to
get teachers to understand.

